Structurally, by creating two classes, one for the original code (KeystoneAuth) and another for the new code (KeystoneAuthEx), it means that going forward, we effectively have two sets of authorization code to maintain. Each time a feature is proposed, there will be a debate whether it should only be added to the new policy code or also apply to the older code. Every time a suspected bug is reported, we first have to find out whether the end-user has configured a policy so that we know which code to examine. And having examined one set of code, we then need to read the other code just to make sure the bug is not also there.

I have a proposal: use the policy file logic as the core of the new code. To support the legacy options, you construct a policy with something such as:

    def __init__(...
        ...
        self._operator_roles = self._conf.get('operator_roles', 'admin, swiftoperator').lower()
        self._reseller_admin_role = self._conf.get('reseller_admin_role', 'ResellerAdmin').lower()
        self._policy_file = conf.get('policy_file', None)
        self._polcy_rules = None
        if not self._policy_file:
            self._policy_rules = _get_default_json_file()  # copied from your tests
            self._policy_rules['reseller_admin_roles'] = ' or '.join[['role:%s' % role for role in self._reseller_admin_role]])
            self._policy_rules['operator_roles'] = ' or '.join[['role:%s' % role for role in self._operator_roles]])

and later, when constructing the Enforcer

       enforcer = Enforcer(policy_file=self._policy_file, rules=self._policy_rules)

In effect, you use the legacy options in the new environment.

As-is, the gate functional tests do not exercise any of your code. If you use my suggestion, the gate functional tests would exercise the new code. The changes would also be easier to review -- we would be able to see what was changed. As-is, it's already hard to see if there were any changes in the legacy code path since that code moved to a new location in the keystoneauth.py"}, {'account_id': 12193, 'date': '2015-02-05 11:03:45.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 12193, 'date': '2015-02-05 11:10:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-05 11:33:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified-1

@Donagh, Thanks for the review.
As for the structure of the module, I think your point is covered by KeystoneAuthBase class which has common methods and filter_factory. If two functionality within one class, it become big and KeystoneAuth should be remove after policy-based RBAC become default. Maybe further discussion is needed.

The sample policy.json file is so complicated that I'm not sure it's usable. It should be possible to read it and know whether it's correct or not. I've spent at least an hour looking at that file and while I think I spotted something wrong (see next comment), I've not convinced myself that it *is* correct and that there is no regression in functionality.

I'm fairly sure that it does not handle the difference between .rlistings and .r;* -- yet all tests pass. This suggests that the tests (unit, functional and/or tempest) are not exercising all cases.

I have not yet done  a detailed review. While I am familiar with the code, the last time I changed it I did not need to worry about ACLs so I'm not familiar with that code, so a detailed review will take more time."}, {'account_id': 12193, 'date': '2015-05-08 06:16:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

(11 comments)

Donagh, Thanks for the review and give me a lot of useful comments. I really appreciate it.

> The sample policy.json file is so complicated that I'm not sure it's usable. It should be possible to read it and know whether it's correct or not. I've spent at least an hour looking at that file and while I think I spotted something wrong (see next comment), I've not convinced myself that it *is* correct and that there is no regression in functionality.

The current keystoneauth logic is complicated for changing oslo.policy based logic. So my idea is hide some logic which is not necessary for operators in policy.json. I will think about it and also with your comments the policy file might be more simpler so I will think it too. 

> I'm fairly sure that it does not handle the difference between .rlistings and .r;* -- yet all tests pass. This suggests that the tests (unit, functional and/or tempest) are not exercising all cases.

I think I implemented it in authorize_unconfirmed_identity.
If it is not covered the current logic, please let me know.

I will work this patch with the following procedure.
* fix bugs which you found out
* brush up current policy.json
* split the policy.json to two parts

Thanks again!"}, {'account_id': 860, 'date': '2015-05-08 11:09:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

I see that. So authorize_unconfirmed_identity() is the wrong place to make that distinction. (6 comments)

I think it's an *amazing* idea for the keystoneauth middleware to support policy.json

I think it's fine for the keystoneauth middleware to require oslo.cofig - the auth_token middleware already does - so if you're using keystone you already have it installed/packaged.

It's not clear to me in this patch why we're lumping using policy.json together with transitioning the configuration of the keystoneauth middleware to oslo.config.

I think we should split up this up - it all depends on our goals.

If we're interested in making policy.json and oslo_policy work - GREAT - let's do that - i have some tactical comments inline that should make it pretty simple to do.

If we're interested in transitioning some or all of our middleware configuration to oslo.config that's a separate thing and shouldn't also be adding the policy.json/oslo_policy stuff at the same time.

If there is some reason we think we can't do keystone+policy.json unless we let keystone configure itself via oslo.config - I don't see it.

Please get *real* specific about our goals.  What are we doing here?"}, {'account_id': 12193, 'date': '2015-06-18 09:19:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15:

(6 comments)

Clay, thanks for the review. I realized this patch lacks direction when I read your advice so I would remove the logic for transitioning the configuration and forcus on making policy.json and oslo_policy work. And with your technical advices I think this patch becomes more simple.

Current Status: 
As a result of discussion with Alistair and Donagh at the design summit, I have been working on making functional tests for access controls on current master because this patch will change all authentication logic. And current policy.json is difficult to understand because of rule's granularity and it's Engilish name. And also today, there is an email in openstack-dev (http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/067301.html). I will update the patch with it. 
Test Patterns (combination of the following patterns):
    APIs:                           http://paste.openstack.org/show/301002/
    Static Configuration Patterns : http://paste.openstack.org/show/301003/
    Dynamic Configuration Patterns: http://paste.openstack.org/show/301004/

I will work on this with following procedure:
(1) Update this patch based on Clay's tech advices
(2) Update this patch based on the email (naming rule for actions)
(3) Create functional tests
(4) Update the rule's granularity and it's Engilish name

(3) and (4) will do parallel if possible."}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-06-19 04:50:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15:

(10 comments)

Thanks for your responses - really pushed me to dig in some more.

I'm trying to follow the links.

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/067301.html

... didn't seem as interesting as 

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/065656.html

http://paste.openstack.org/show/301002/ - is everything we want to test
http://paste.openstack.org/show/301003/ - is some permutations of some configs we want to validate
but http://paste.openstack.org/show/301004/ i dont' get - obviously you want to test some different acl strings - but that list of 300 things doesn't make sense - 1 & 2 are literally the same values all the way across.

OK!  So I'm glad to hear you picked oslo_policy as the focus - a feature!  So much more fun than a refactoring of our config parsing.  I think there's some actual real live value in a policy engine.  Since the goal is simplicity rip out as much of that middleware oslo.config stuff as possible.

Moving on to policy.json - we need to figure out what we're trying to accomplish - I don't think we should review all these changes and maintain a bunch of interop with external libraries just for it to work exactly the same way - we need to solve some use case!

I think this change needs some doc.

What is are the primary use-cases we want solve for swift operators that can be enabled by policy.json that we couldn't do with-out a policy engine?

I'm starting to think it might be easier to spike on an implementation of some of the policy.json handling against tempauth since it's authentication rules are a *little* simpler and have less legacy cruft.  It seems like the get_(action|target|creds) helpers - while simple - are something that a *lot* of different auth middleware could take advantage of if that want to move toward a configurable policy engine for authorization.

... anyway - good luck with the tests!"}, {'account_id': 12193, 'date': '2015-07-17 05:24:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

(8 comments)

I got an abandon alert so I put comments which are prepared for submitting next patch.'}, {'account_id': 12193, 'date': '2015-07-17 05:28:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15:

Clay, thanks for you review. I'm working on functional test now. After I will finish it I will restart this."}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2015-10-20 21:11:58.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Abanoning based on the lack of activity since the last negative review. If you want to continue working on this, please reopen this patch.'}, {'account_id': 12193, 'date': '2015-10-21 01:40:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15:

re-open this patch
I have been working for functional test of rbac and it's prerequisite of this patch. After the functional test patches are landed I will re-start this patch."}]

[{'created': '2015-01-26 06:15:11.000000000', 'message': "Enable Role-based access control using oslo.policy in Swift

This patch realizes Role-based access control (RBAC) with Keystone
using oslo.policy library in Swift.

All keystoneauth authorisations logic were translated into json
policy format, to ensure backward compatibly.

The oslo.policy library was in oslo-incubator but this library
will be graduated in Kilo-2 milestones (Feb. 5).
Until the milestones the current entry for the library in
'test-requirement.txt' should be temporary one.
https://github.com/openstack/oslo-specs/blob/master/specs/kilo/graduate-policy.r

How does it work:
* Either 'reseller_admin_role' or 'operator_roles' is specified
  in proxy-server.conf, RBAC works with the parameters.
* Neither 'reseller_admin_role' nor 'operator_roles' is not specified
  in proxy-server.conf and 'policy_file' is specided the configuration
  file,  RBAC works with specified policy file.
* When the default policy file (default_policy.json) is used, both
  behavior should be same.

Change-Id: Ia55b81cc14c9bf917c402e5a00c08365e4d340b1
Implements: blueprint updated-authorization-policy

commit_message:
WIP: Enable Role-based access control using oslo.policy in Swift

This patch realizes Role-based access control (RBAC) with Keystone
using oslo.policy library in Swift.

All keystoneauth authorisations logic were translated into json
policy format, to ensure backward compatibly.

Note that deployers need to specify a policy file which is created by
themselves. There is a default policy file which is stored in
/etc/swift/policy.json. The policy file can be a base of their cluster.

How does it work:
* keystoneauth works with a policy file which is specified in
  proxy-server.conf as policy_file.
* If 'reseller_admin_role', 'operator_roles' and 'service_roles' are
  specified in proxy-server.conf, keystoneauth updates the policy
  with the information and works with it.

Notes:
* oslo.policy seems to be not supported HTTP_X_SERVICE_ROLES so
  I created ServiceRoleCheck class but it is better to have it
  in the library. I will get in touch with oslo.policy guys about
  it.
* the method '_get_policy_json_file' in keystoneauth.py will be
  removed because this is only for backward compatibility of the
  gate.

Change-Id: Ia55b81cc14c9bf917c402e5a00c08365e4d340b1
Implements: blueprint updated-authorization-policy

commit_message:
Use testtools for base test class

The testtools library has been chosen as the project-wide testing base
class. It works across 2.6 and 2.7 and is a library that aims to develop
new testing features before inclusion in the standard library.

Change-Id: Id712f8ac6cade539a97d18e00f9dc7c584b29c99
Closes-Bug: #1179009

commit_message:
[install] remove Fedora from the install guide

According to
https://www.redhat.com/archives/rdo-list/2015-October/msg00234.html
OpenStack packages for Fedora will only provided through the
Delorean repository.

More details at https://trello.com/c/wzdl1IlZ/52-openstack-in-fedora:

---snip---
Fedora users (assumed to be developers who want latest code and not
running production) will use Delorean Trunk for Fedora repos.
---snap---

Change-Id: I1220fae10c6c212b6aab347d9886238e89200799

commit_message:
Port swift.common.utils.backward() to Python 3

backward() is written to handle binary files:

* Replace literal native strings to literal byte strings: add b'...'
  prefix
* Update unit tests: use byte strings
* TemporaryFile(): use the default mode 'w+b', instead of using 'r+w'
  ('r+w' mode creates a Unicode file on Python 3).

Change-Id: Ic91f7e6c605db0b888763080d49f0f501029837f

commit_message:
devref doc: assorted fixes in "Unit Tests"

Fix the example command for running a unit test.
(Colon versus period.)

Fix box formatting for tox commands.  (Need extra
newline after double colon.)

Fix a typo in the same section.

Fix broken ostestr doc link.

Remove testr and flake8 links that don't go anywhere.

Change-Id: I243e4f0639ef4a87e8950e0428b7556919094b0e

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-14 21:35:25.000000000', 'message': "Fix AttributeError on port_bound for missing ports

If the port is concurrently deleted, db_get_val returns None, and
that causes the Exception to be raised. However, the exception is just
log noise if the port has been deleted concurrently.

This can happen if port_update and port_delete operations can happen
in short sequence and can interleave. To prevent this trace from
occurring, this patch checks that the port is being eliminated and
emits an error trace only if the port is indeed to be expected.

We avoid raising an exception to avoid disrupting the agent sync
process and leave to the admin the investigation of the issue
(should that be cronic rather than transient).

Under normal circumnstances, if the port is expected it should
be there, and if it isn't this should be treated as a bug to be
investigated further.

Closes-bug: #1455320

Change-Id: Ic609af0ef6a09b536c882c58c23167c0a469b155

If the port is concurrently deleted, db_get_val returns None, and
that causes the Exception to be raised. However, the exception is just
log noise if the port has been deleted concurrently and it does not
lead to failures.

This can happen if port_update and port_delete operations occur
in short sequence and interleave. To prevent this trace from
occurring, this patch checks that the port is being eliminated and
emits an error trace only if the port is indeed to be expected

process, and leave to the admin the investigation of the issue
(should that be cronic rather than transient).

be there, and if it isn't this should be treated as a bug to be
investigated further.

commit_message:
Fix AttributeError on port_bound for missing ports

If the port is concurrently deleted, db_get_val returns None, and
that causes the Exception to be raised. However, the exception is just
log noise if the port has been deleted concurrently and it does not
lead to failures.

This can happen if port_update and port_delete operations occur
in short sequence and interleave. To prevent this trace from
occurring, this patch checks that the port is being eliminated and
emits an error trace only if the port is indeed to be expected
amongst the list of ports to be updated.

We do not raise an exception to avoid disrupting the agent sync
process, and leave to the admin the investigation of the issue
(should that be cronic rather than transient).

Under normal circumstances, if the port is expected it should
be there, and if it isn't this should be treated as a bug to be
investigated further.

Closes-bug: #1455320

Change-Id: Ic609af0ef6a09b536c882c58c23167c0a469b155

commit_message:
Improving JS unit test branch coverage

This patch is testing untested branches.

There is a bug in the Launch Instance model where it is supposed to
remove null properties from the top level of the model.  It is not doing
that properly.  So that bug is also fixed.

This patch currently raises the branch coverage in openstack_dashboard
from ~84% to ~89%.

Closes-bug: 1506891
Change-Id: I7434126246b15209b62daeff75744e0a3b435494

commit_message:
Remove StandardError for Python3

As in python3 the StandardError exception has been removed, we
should use BaseException instead of it.

Change-Id: I0d7a3fe773c827bc81f816e84ba3549fc123af9f

commit_message:
Avoid mocking oslo internal

Change: Mocking HttpCheck rather than the more general urlrequest
Backport of this fix: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/233506
Updated semantic version to 2.0.1

Purpose: Fixes a test broken by oslo.policy release.
Without the fix py27 gating fails in liberty as follows:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/234495/

Change-Id: I623d19a75518b9a9a42122041e2719ff4e54cd56

commit_message:
Skip bad meter definitions instead of erroring out

Currently we raise an exception once we hit a bad
meter definition in the yaml. Instead, skip the
bad ones and proceed with rest of the yaml.

Closes-Bug: #1503433

Change-Id: I1dd5b69bf9a92b5af5692ea75010f11a863b0afc
(cherry picked from commit 5d5aaf58c8876370ff9729e08b3b41833f6e6efc)

commit_message:
Pagination limit code refactor

The logic to find the pagination limit is
repeated several times and is not in one
function. This patch creates a function that
is called in various locations replacing
repetitive code.

Change-Id: I3eced6a4236e4189e57ea5a1589e8f0d411cc4e3
Closes-Bug:  #1308285

commit_message:
Explain default domain in docs for other services

The documentation for other services previously made an assertion that
(paraphrasing) "using v3 tokens on v2 works fine." That statement comes
with a laundry list of caveats, starting with the "default" domain.

This patch revises the documentation to introduce the default domain
first, and then enumerates the caveats that come as a result of mixing
and matching v2 and v3.

There's also some general RST syntax improvements, grammar improvements,
and line wrapping politely at 79 characters like your mother taught you
to do.

Change-Id: I342092b9c9971d44438fa83f547d1f5ddd204ced

commit_message:
Sets loaded rule info to Rule instances

Policy Engine initializes Rule instances when Congress starts
if rules are persited in db. The bug is that Policy Engine only
loads persited rule string but doesn't set other infomation,
id, name and comment. This patch lets Policy Engine set the
lacked infomations to Rule instance.

Closes-Bug: #1507329
Change-Id: Id8354d9bff0d5b5938406473e2f344e726bd2f3c

commit_message:
Revise nova server get_details call

This patch revises the get_details call for the nova server profile. The
goal is to make the output looks more closer to that of nova show
command. Another reason is that we need to expose all attributes of a
nova server so that some policies (such as placement policy) can check
the required attributes (e.g. availability zone of a node).

Change-Id: I438a01c8910f3bfc071ff1e71389b454d0c94662

MItaka version should be 6.0, why do we change it to 0.1?'}, {'account_id': 7404, 'date': '2015-10-19 15:00:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hmm, seems version 6.0 is just for heat.'}, {'account_id': 7404, 'date': '2015-10-19 15:03:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Just curious that can we change this version option multiple times in one release?'}, {'account_id': 7404, 'date': '2015-10-19 15:09:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Seems kolla also initial their version to 0.1.0 at the beginning of liberty, and change version to 1.0.0 at the end of liberty. I think we can do that too.'}, {'account_id': 8246, 'date': '2015-10-19 15:22:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

A bit of explanation about version numbers. The first release of a software has to be a 0.1 for pypi to accept it. I learned this in the hard way when creating releases for python-senlinclient. After the first release, the project team can decide on a proper version scheme and bump versions as necessary.

The difference between "2016.1" and "6.0.0" is that it was recently proposed to switch to semver version scheme in the community. Each project will automatically switch to a new version number after the 2015.1 release. The version for a project is based on its history being released by the community. For example, Nova is now 13.0.0 because Nova has been there for 13 cycles. Glance may be 8.0.0 because it has been there for 8 cycles.

For Senlin, our first official release (when adopted by Big Tent) should be 1.0.0.

If you still don't understand the model, check this: http://docs.openstack.org/releases/releases/liberty.html

Yes, it would be a disaster. In future, you will be asking questions like where you are using Heat 5.0.0 instead of Heat Liberty. But when you are talking about Nova, it would be version 12.0'}, {'account_id': 11034, 'date': '2015-10-20 01:44:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks for the explanation, just learned more :)'}, {'account_id': 8246, 'date': '2015-10-21 00:18:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-21 00:18:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

Mark branch as 0.1

We need a branch version 0.1 to create the first release. Then we can
target 1.0 as an official release during mitaka cycle.

commit_message:
Search the list of servers with unicode text.

Searching the list of servers with a a string with unicode string,
throws an exception (urlencode). The fix properly encode the
search string.

Change-Id: I8f2fd6a7b8e337a61b02963ededf1d1b5ad5b6ae
Closes-Bug: #1472999

commit_message:
Add region resource to identity service

This patch proposes adding region as resources for the identity service.
The keystone v3 API exposes all necessary interfaces for region
management. Supporting regions is important for multi-region
deployments.

Change-Id: Ie44f3b60c292769f77944b3da0de215888ca83c8

commit_message:
Strips off the quotes when showing nested table

When showing a nested table, the current formatting logic preserves the
quote marks when displaying a JSON or sometimes a string. This patch
proposes a change to strip of the quotes so the values are shown in more
consistent way.

Change-Id: Ib4b6cd0e941afee456469e1ce2986c1dddb5134f

commit_message:
Set cache information from clouds.yaml

With 1.9.0 of os-client-config, there are appropriate methods
on the cloud_config object which allow access to cache config settings.
Additionally, there is a documented mechanism for passing in
per-resource cache timing, for things like list_servers.

Depends-On: I352f827715821db8a69983eae0ee3e9c8c99f512
Change-Id: Iba9af1cdddf0844c885ff203f67a522dc451a3ed

Change-Id: Ib495afc79229ab0bb9f9eb40388c00a618b84cb1

commit_message:
Fix Murano delete environment

Environment is deleted instatly from murano DB after delete API
request is finished:
https://github.com/openstack/murano/blob/0ced0071095248283ec4f95aadeaea962e096fa9/murano/api/v1/environments.py#L158-L173

It means next thing:
* We shouldn't use wait_for in this case
* We should use SynchronizedDeletion in resource cleanup
* We shouldn't make hacks in get_status() to make this work

This patch cleans up conf options as well

Change-Id: Ib495afc79229ab0bb9f9eb40388c00a618b84cb1

commit_message:
Support Neutron 'q-flavors' plugin

With the Neutron flavors framework as a regular services plugin,
need ability to enable service as part of DevStack.

Change-Id: I7e667aa64990c1d3009973bf3f093797e40ad4f9
Depends-On: I5c22ab655a8e2a2e586c10eae9de9b72db49755f
Implements: blueprint neutron-flavor-framework

commit_message:
Remove jeepyb and pypi-mirror from PROJECTS

These two projects were used as part of the setup for the
requirements/pbr testing but that is no longer the case. In fact
requirements and pbr both have special casing to ignore these projects
in the PROJECTS list now. Remove them to shorten the PROJECTS list which
simplifies test run workspace setup.

Change-Id: I61c2f3f8a724dc789479278e7ba493e095c52305

Pin puppet-heat

The current puppet-heat module has a regression effecting tripleo.
Pin it while we either revert or fix.

commit_message:
Use the liberty release RDO RPMS

Previously stable/liberty was using the Delorean repositories for
installing RPM packaging.  Delorean is master, and up until just about
now that made sense, but going forward, we want to use the Liberty
release of RDO rather then Mitaka for stable/liberty ;)

Closes-Bug: #1508127

Change-Id: I675c434d25419853bb3ce6442d1b4db6ea448af0

[{'created': '2015-10-20 20:28:20.000000000', 'message': 'Increase Ceph RPM gpg key timeout to 90 seconds

The default timeout for Ceph GPG rpm key retrieval is 30 seconds.
In my testing, the GPG key takes approximately 50 seconds to download
often resulting in a failure to build containers that need to retrieve
the Ceph GPG sign key.  Crank up the timer to 90 seconds so the key
is more likely to be downloaded, allowing images to be built.

backport: liberty

TrivialFix

Change-Id: I7420cdf8d3b61aa9f4f52795fccbe5da3e48d57b
'}]
commit_message:
Increase Ceph RPM gpg key timeout to 90 seconds

The default timeout for Ceph GPG rpm key retrieval is 30 seconds.
In my testing, the GPG key takes approximately 50 seconds to download
often resulting in a failure to build containers that need to retrieve
the Ceph GPG sign key.  Crank up the timer to 90 seconds so the key
is more likely to be downloaded, allowing images to be built.

backport: liberty

TrivialFix

Change-Id: I7420cdf8d3b61aa9f4f52795fccbe5da3e48d57b

commit_message:
Fix tests/test_functions.bash

I am not sure why we didn't hit it before, but
1. The command is 'docker images', not 'docker image'
2. Calling 'docker rmi' requires a check on image presence

Change-Id: I127359043f975a25bb1bfad7469dfe01be67e2d9

commit_message:
Support the format of crash dump directory for RHEL7.1 and CentOS7.1

Currently, crash checks support only below format.
YYYYMMddHHmm (e.g. 201509032311)
Support the format of RHEL7.1 and CentOS7.1.
<IP-address>-YYYY.MM.dd-HH:mm:ss (e.g. 127.0.0.1-2015.10.02-16:07:51)

Change-Id: Ia023edc3505e584200b043814480bfcfbd60920c
Closes-Bug: #1500766

commit_message:
Correct MAC representation to match iptables output

We were previously using the netaddr's mac_unix format
(which leaves off leading 0's) to generate iptables rules
based on MAC addresses. While iptables accepts this format,
it's not returned this way in the output so the iptables
rule matching code would never find the match for these
rules, causing the loss of counters on these rules on every
reload.

This patch corrects this with a custom dialect that matches
the iptables format.

Closes-Bug: #1502901
Change-Id: Ia45ebde8c4684e12030469323e18367a54d1518b
(cherry picked from commit 5cab062465af06be3827de4e7f9014ab1040bdbf)

commit_message:
support mysql+pymysql in functional test

Currently, if we use PyMySQL as MySQL driver, database connection
url will be set to mysql+pymysql://, but our functional test doesn't
recognize such engine name, which finally will skip all the functional
test for mysql backend.

This patch simply maps mysql+pymysql to mysql.

Change-Id: I924de57e9f194f183a405846a6ac98968a2483d3
Closes-Bug: #1506777
(cherry picked from commit bf85df219e02dd1203457eb88eda32b3871aa3c4)

the given timeout of 10 seconds to list thr available instances
is not enough. Increase the timeout to not run into

Change-Id: Ie2345e6858bcc97095863d5d388bacf9c29b7682

commit_message:
Increase timeout when testing admin timeout

When running functional tests in a slow virtual environment,
the given timeout of 10 seconds to list thr available instances
is not enough. Increase the timeout to not run into
a "timed out (HTTP 408)".

Change-Id: Ie2345e6858bcc97095863d5d388bacf9c29b7682

commit_message:
Update paths due to stackforge migration.

fuel-library repository has been moved from stackforge/ to openstack/ namespace.

fuel-tasklib repository got deprecated during migration, but it appears it is
still used in fuel-library CI. We add temporary workaround to run CI job
using fuel-tasklib package from fixed commit. The problem will be properly resolved
via related bug #1507208.

Change-Id: I8e2342c869a27fa1bb104fd46138ad27270f2d73
Related-Bug: #1507208

commit_message:
Allow ctlplane network or ID, and default to "ctlplane"

Currently you always have to pass the ctlplane ID because we're still
using the deprecated network_id property for the neutron port resource.

Since Juno, heat has supported a "network" property, which is used
elsewhere, e.g the nested port stacks, so switch to using it in the
overcloud-without-mergepy template, and flip the default to a more
useful "ctlplane" vs an empty string.

This means the stack create should just work on commonly documented
deployments without requiring any parameter.

Change-Id: Ifcea36d26b795c5e8b80accd8112e23b254127be

Replace Bunch with compatible fork Munch

- check-grenade-dsvm http://logs.openstack.org/93/180893/2/check/check-grenade-dsvm/c781099/ : SUCCESS in 39m 10s
- check-swift-dsvm-functional http://logs.openstack.org/93/180893/2/check/check-swift-dsvm-functional/04723ab/ : SUCCESS in 19m 05s'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2015-05-07 15:22:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I tried to enumerate the scenarios in which we get  replication_count = 0 at the end of a complete run:

 1. there were no jobs (due to override_* options) - does that require a warning?
 2. all jobs fail mount_check -> warning already logged
 3. all jobs fail ring change check -> info already logged
 4. all job paths are files -> warning already logged
 5. all jobs hit some other OSError -> nothing logged

Maybe I am nit-picking but if there is to be a change to warning might it be worth distinguishing between 'no jobs found' and 'all jobs had error'?"}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-05-07 19:23:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

That informational message is NOT a warning.  We shouldn't log it as such.  If our INFO log level is so noisy people don't want to run at INFO then there's probably some INFO log lines that should be DEBUG.

If you're running at warning then you *should* expect logs to be *super* quiet - unless something is broken (kudos to you for trusting the system so much; but I'm skeptical that's really the best plan; an aggressive logrotate schedule would probably work out better IMHO).

OTOH, if we think that stats line is just more important than your average info log message we could add a separately configurable stats_logger (like we do with the access logger in the proxy logging middleware) which you can turn down the log level to info and leave the main logger at warning (again - skeptical).

Or - maybe cheaper - I also know that log levels are just integers - maybe we could bump up that line ever so slightly and these configs that want warnings + stats line can turn their log level just low enough to pick up that elevated message."}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2015-05-08 06:35:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Alistair, Clay: thanks for your review!

My intention with this patch was to raise the loglevel only for the final stats_line that gets send out after the replicator has finished its job, and only if nothing got replicated at all.

If you're running with the default info level I want to see that message pop out somehow out of all the other info messages. I think it is important to notice this message asap.

What I recently saw was a node that was working behind some NAT, thus the IP in the ring builder didn't match the host IP - and the host just found no jobs to do. I noticed a similar behavior in a virtualized lab setup shortly after.
I was looking into adding some logging if no jobs are found, but then this happens sometimes because you restrict jobs to a specific policy and the like.

If someone starts with a small virtualized cluster without much experience in Swift yet, it looks ok if the replicator just says "Btw, nothing hot replicated, but it's just an info". It's a completely different thing if there is a "Hey there, this is a warning: nothing got replicated!" - operators will then look at this, because you normally watch out for warnings.

So, I'd like to see some kind of warning here.

Please let me know how to continue on this.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-13 11:03:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 16233, 'date': '2015-05-13 14:08:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 2696, 'date': '2015-05-15 06:17:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

That sounds like a legit issue to be able to notice and warn about.

But maybe it'd be better to explicitly look for and log about the situation: "None of the devices in the ring(s) seem to be on this server, this could be a misconfiguration between ring IPs and my server IPs".  That might communicate to the operator more clearly than a random informational-looking log line that happens to be at level WARNING instead of INFO.'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2015-10-20 21:14:41.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Abanoning based on the lack of activity since the last negative review. If you want to continue working on this, please reopen this patch.'}]

commit_message:
Increase replicator log level if nothing got replicated

Sometimes nothing is replicated at all, and if an operator set the loglevel to
warning only this will not show up in the logs.
This patch increases the log level to warning, but only for the final call to
stats_line() of the replication run; intermediate calls to stats_line() executed
by the heartbeat method are still logging using the info loglevel.

Also add two simple tests for stats_line, checking calculated output.

Change-Id: I6fe46bdd1a02481211a6eda9978e816881446fc1

commit_message:
Swift-Storlets - allowing dynamic compute functions

A new middleware for Openstack Swift allowing to dynamically add
compute functions along the pipeline, without the need to epxlicitly
add new middleware.

Code reference can be found here:
    https://github.com/Open-I-Beam/swift-storlets

Change-Id: I273d23db6e9373a71115e4b685cc1dfe9536f063

commit_message:
Additional exit codes for swift-drive-audit

Encode the swift-drive-audit result and the actions performed in the exit
status, in particular if a drive was unmounted or was not available.

Closes-Bug: #1359664
Change-Id: Id230082dd59e935aa81f10e98852b89d914a17de

Don't we already support zero interrupt restarts with reload/HUP?

main process calls listen and hands socket of to forked workers to wait on accept, when you reload the main process stops listening and any processes blocked in accept will terminate but existing connections will finish, meanwhile a new main process is restarted to again call listen.

I haven't looked at the patch and am not familiar with the system call - but before I start digging into all of that I want to understand the functional behavior that this change would enable so I can verify it's doing what it says and that it's saying it can do something I can't do today."}, {'account_id': 13852, 'date': '2014-12-05 08:53:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

With the current behavior, as you described, sending a HUP will (gently) terminate the server. Then, another server must be started. It means that during that short interval, no processes are listening for incoming requests.

On our clusters, each config change or code upgrade meant thousands of requests refused because of that short downtime.

With the REUSEPORT option, it is possible to start a new instance of the server before sending the HUP to the old process. It means that there is always, at least, one process listening for incoming requests. So, it ensure that no requests are refused => zero downtime.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2014-12-05 21:24:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Is there anyway this new capability (the --finish-pid option i guess) could be baked into swift-init reload or the manager - or maybe that already works somehow?  If not, maybe a custom init script that don't use swift-init directly could work - maybe you could point me at something or tell me more about what you're thinking...

Is there any room in the admin guide to add some more information about using the feature (again assume the audience is a fumbling johnny devops newb like myself).

This looks good to me, +1 for now. However, one question: why is it necessary to check plaform, instead of verify that socket has SO_REUSEPORT (with getattr or such)? It looked to me that Linux's SO_REUSEPORT is pretty well compatible with the old BSD's one, so most likely OSX has a good one too."}, {'account_id': 13780, 'date': '2015-02-19 15:04:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1

Good for me'}, {'account_id': 7479, 'date': '2015-02-21 23:04:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2

works for me!'}, {'account_id': 13852, 'date': '2015-02-24 16:14:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

> verify that socket has SO_REUSEPORT (with getattr or such)

1/ Attribute socket.SO_REUSEPORT was introduced in Python 2.7.5. It is always present, no matter the kernel version. So, if you have a Python >= 2.7.5 but a Linux kernel < 3.9, the code will think reuseport is available, but it won't be.

2/ Some Linux distributions still come with Python < 2.7.5 (at least Debian 7 and Ubuntu 12.04 which is the recommendation for SAIO). So, if you install a recent kernel on these distributions, you have the possibility to use reuseport, but your Python would not have the attribute socket.SO_REUSEPORT. (actually, it's my case)

3/ It must be assumed that the value of socket.SO_REUSEPORT is different for each OS. So, for Python < 2.7.5, the correct way would be to check versions of OS and set the correct value. I just don't have the resources (hardware/time) to test all the possibilities, and I don't think enabling something untested is a good idea.

So, using getattr() for now is not an option I think, but it could be in the future. Question is what are the required versions of Python and OS to run Swift? If the requirement is "An OS that support REUSEPORT + Python >= 2.7.5", then it is an option.'}, {'account_id': 9625, 'date': '2015-02-24 21:58:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1

works! thanks for the updates'}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2015-02-24 23:41:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

(1 comment)

Fine, that explains the case of 15 constant, but  why can't you try and apply SO_REUSEADDR if it exists, and ignore it if a certain error occurs?"}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-03-03 03:27:59.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-03-03 03:32:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

just a rebase...

However, this implementation doesn't deal with upgrades very well IMHO.  If you try to `swift-init proxy reload` the processes that were started with master it will fail (SO_REUSEPORT only works if the first process to bind there also used SO_REUSEPORT), and as a side effect of how swift-init handles failures with start it also orphan those pids.

Given that as maybe a good enough reason to continue work on this change there's a few other tactical things I also find myself worried about.

1) We're leaking process management into the daemon scripts themselves.  All of that functionality is currently handled in the Manager/Server classes, and I think it'd be easier to avoid accidentally breaking some slightly-away-from-the-norm init script if we keep it there.  As implemented the --terminate/finish options still expose all the burden of pid tracking to the caller, leaving only the "hiding" of HUP vs. TERM which seems like a small value IMHO.  If someone wants to use this functionality and roll their own thing the only part they *need* is for the wsgi servers to setsockopt when it can.

2) We're extracting eventlet's listen into the middle of our get_socket function - since we need to reimplement it so we can add socket options before calling bind I think we should endeavor to make it as true to the original re-implementation as possible to ease maintenance until we get something added upstream (maybe an add_extra_socket_options callback param?)

3)  I almost always advocate for EAFP over LBYL, and from the wsgi server's perspective it's probably better to always try and set the socket option and squelch the error when it's not available.  The presence of the attribute on the python socket module seems to be related to the header files that were available when the interpreter was compiled - the precise 2.7.3 definitely does not have it while trusty's 2.7.6 does (trusty's python 3.4.2 surprisingly does not).

I believe issues 1 & 2 (and to a lesser extent 3) can be resolved in my mind with a cleanup aimed at taking on the issue with upgrade:

    https://review.openstack.org/#/c/160621/

^ I didn't attempt to rollback the tests changes nor add new tests for reload - so if you want to roll any of that diff into here I'd be happy to abandon.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-03 04:21:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified+1

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-11-27 15:03:24.000000000', 'message': 'Support of the Linux socket option SO_REUSEPORT

Linux, since version 3.9, added a new option for TCP and UDP sockets:
SO_REUSEPORT. Multiple processes can bind to the same port if they
each set the SO_REUSEPORT option.

This feature have two usages. It loadbalances the traffic over
multiple processes, usefull when the server is not multithreaded. It
also helps to provide a zero-downtime restart. Zero-downtime restart
is the main objective of that patch.

The new configuration option DEFAULT/reuseport, available for
account|container|object|proxy server, enables the socket option if
the kernel is a Linux>=3.9. It is disabled by default.

The new runtime options --finish=<pid> and --terminate=<pid> send,
respectively, the signals SIGHUP and SIGTERM to the pid specified.

To execute a zero-downtime restart, a new server must be started with
the --finish=$PID option, where $PID is the pid of the currently
running process.

Example, for a proxy server:
    /usr/bin/python /usr/bin/swift-proxy-server \
        /etc/swift/proxy-server.conf \
        --finish $(cat /var/run/swift/proxy-server.pid)

Change-Id: I3a6cd3635545402203fa8c5de0c43ede81fb7c0e

commit_message:
Support of the Linux socket option SO_REUSEPORT

To reload servers processes, the current behavior is to send a HUP to the
process that will (gently) terminate the server. Then, another server must be
started. It means that during that short interval, no processes are listening
for incoming requests.

Linux, since version 3.9, added a new option for TCP and UDP sockets:
SO_REUSEPORT. Multiple processes can bind to the same port if they
each set the SO_REUSEPORT option.

This feature have two usages. It loadbalances the traffic over
multiple processes, useful when the server is not multithreaded. It
also helps to provide a zero-downtime restart by allowing that, at any time,
there is always at least one process listening for incoming requests.
Zero-downtime restart is the main objective of that patch.

The new behavior is to enable the socket option, when available, for
account|container|object|proxy server. The option is considered available when
the underlying OS is Linux>=3.9.

The new runtime options --finish=<pid> and --terminate=<pid> send,
respectively, the signals SIGHUP and SIGTERM to the pid specified.

To execute a zero-downtime restart, a new server must be started with
the --finish=$PID option, where $PID is the pid of the currently
running process.

Example, for a proxy server:
    /usr/bin/python /usr/bin/swift-proxy-server \
        /etc/swift/proxy-server.conf \
        --finish $(cat /var/run/swift/proxy-server.pid)

The swift-init command is modified to use these options when appropriate.

Change-Id: I3a6cd3635545402203fa8c5de0c43ede81fb7c0e

commit_message:
object-replicator warns when object dirs mismatch with policy settings

Currently, object-replicator runs only for 'objects-<policy_idx>'
directories whose 'idx' is defined in swift.conf. This means that, for
example, if there are 'objects', 'objects-1' and 'objects-2' directories
in some devices but swift.conf only contains [storage-policy:0] and
[storage-policy:1] sections, object-replicator does not seek 'objects-2'
directory.

However, operators cannot be noticed that replicator does not work for
'objects-2' dir because there is no log output. Therefore, this can cause
delay in detecting config mismatches among swift servers or other
unexpected situations and then, in the worst case, this can cause data
losses.

This patch enables to output logs in the case of the mismatch between
object directory infomation and swift.conf. This mismatch check process
is executed after the completion of replication processes because the
sooner a replicator process starts the better.

Change-Id: Ie005775a626f12b0d0fb339533e63918978a89f2
Related-Bug: 1375438

[{'created': '2015-02-25 20:35:10.000000000', 'message': 'Sync local regions first, and always shuffle nodes

Move the recently added shuffle nodes call from ObjectReplicator.update under
the common collect_jobs method so it also benifits update and update_deleted.

commit_message:
Sync local regions first, and always shuffle nodes

Move the recently added shuffle nodes call from ObjectReplicator.update under
the common collect_jobs method so it also benifits update and update_deleted.

When primary locations span more than two regions, attempt to sync
cross-region in a deterministic fashion so that efficent replication has the
best chance of an even distribution of WAN traffic (region 0 will push to 1
which will push to 2, then region 0 can delete its handoff).

N.B. the use of region id is only to ensure deterministic ordering, and not
ment to convey any knowledge of region locality, but it theoretically could be
made configurable to handle affinity awareness.

Change-Id: I4b05d2efd647cead4e96d0aca5d89aaf3792aa21

I had forgot about this patch until I found myself really wishing I had a fix for bug #1408061 [1].

I'll fix up the stuff in the tests for sure - thanks.

I'm less sure about the handling of syncing with multiple remote regions.  I think the random node shuffle from the next patch in the chain addresses it somewhat.  But ultimately the semantic is up to us - I like the meme that "a single replication pass will sync to all local nodes and at most one node in a remote region" - feels like an easy way to describe "efficient cross region replication" to me.  But I think there's room for improvement - we may have to expose some configurability and try out different things in practice to see what works - maybe more than one thing would work?

For example - after we release Kilo we may get some bug reports that people liked the old semantic better - "ship everything everywhere all the time!"

Anyway - yeah I get that it's different than how the existing code handles multiple remote regions - but I think it's better because it's simpler.

Maybe not!?  Who knows!  Thanks for the feedback - maybe we can get some more input and still get something in for Kilo...

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-02-25 00:18:48.000000000', 'message': "Cleanup object-replicator handoff/rebalance partition syncing

When removing a partition because of handoff or in response to a
rebalance, remove synced suffixes (and objects) based on the work
performed instead of with rmtree to minimize the impact of a long race
window while syncing the partition to the remote nodes (between the time
when jobs are collected, and the partition is removed).

Since a node which is no longer a primary location does not expect to
receive many updates to the part after a rebalance, this change mainly
effects handoff reversion.  When an object server is accepting writes as
a handoff it's replicator daemon is also trying to remove the partition
from the node after syncing it to the primaries.  If it receives a write
for a new suffix while syncing it will not remove the partition.  If it
is using ssync and receives a write for a different object (hash) while
syncing it will not remove the partition, but an update to a
successfully synced object may still be subject to a race
(clean_suffixes goes object by object, but still uses rmtree without
respect the synced timestamps).

After syncing and removing all suffixes in the partition, the
object-replicator will wait until the subsequent pass to remove the
hashes.pkl, the .lock file, and the otherwise empty partition dir with
rmtree.

Also cleanup the ssync interface for remote check jobs during efficient
cross region replication.

Closes bug #1408061

Change-Id: I40d107c567f02e219f04b1a74d7060f5280432d5

commit_message:
Cleanup object-replicator handoff/rebalance partition syncing

When removing a partition because of handoff or in response to a
rebalance, remove synced suffixes (and objects) based on the work
performed instead of with rmtree to minimize the impact of a long race
window while syncing the partition to the remote nodes (between the time
when jobs are collected, and the partition is removed).

Since a node which is no longer a primary location does not expect to
receive many updates to the part after a rebalance, this change mainly
effects handoff reversion.  When an object server is accepting writes as
a handoff it's replicator daemon is also trying to remove the partition
from the node after syncing it to the primaries.  If it receives a write
for a new suffix while syncing it will not remove the partition.  If it
is using ssync and receives a write for a different object (hash) while
syncing it will not remove the partition, but an update to a
successfully synced object may still be subject to a race
(clean_suffixes goes object by object, but still uses rmtree without
respect the synced timestamps).

After syncing and removing all suffixes in the partition, the
object-replicator will wait until the subsequent pass to remove the
hashes.pkl, the .lock file, and the otherwise empty partition dir with
rmtree.

Also cleanup the ssync interface for remote check jobs during efficient
cross region replication.

Closes bug #1408061

Change-Id: I40d107c567f02e219f04b1a74d7060f5280432d5

I would prefer you either make a bug report that describes the *exact* input to reproduce the unexpected behavior (along with a description of your expected behavior) and associate that bug in the commit message of this change - or a unittest.

Thanks Mark!'}, {'account_id': 7661, 'date': '2015-06-11 18:47:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

thanks clay, makes a lot of sense.

so the help says this:

    Usage: swift-get-nodes [-a] <ring.gz> <account> [<container>] [<object>]
    Or: swift-get-nodes [-a] <ring.gz> -p partition
    Or: swift-get-nodes [-a] -P policy_name <account> <container> <object>

so I'd expect you can't specify -P and a ring at the same time, but you can.

If I do run with both like the following I get an warning and don't think I should:

root@overcloud-ce-controller-swiftstorage0-bqqg7gmpof4n:/tmp# swift-get-nodes /tmp/object-0.ring.gz a b c -P policy-0
Attention! mismatch between ring and policy detected!

now if I leave the policy number off the ring name it's happy:
root@overcloud-ce-controller-swiftstorage0-bqqg7gmpof4n:/tmp# swift-get-nodes /tmp/object.ring.gz a b c -P policy-0

Account  	a
Container	b
Object   	c

and Alistair told me he thought that for backwards comparibility one needed to assume the default was no policy on the ring name but I think both object and object-0 should be acceptable.

but the overarching question is should you be allowed to enter a ring name and -P?  if so, the usage message should be changed."}, {'account_id': 2696, 'date': '2015-06-12 14:37:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

What would it even mean to use -P and a ring on the same command-line?  Isn't -P just a shortcut to help the utility *find* a ring file?  If you're already giving it a ring file, that's redundant at best or mismatching and confusing to the tool at worst.

I'm pretty sure that -P and a ring are mutually exclusive, *semantically*.  It would make sense for the tool enforce that."}, {'account_id': 7661, 'date': '2015-06-12 14:46:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

glad to know I'm not the only one who thinks so.  BUT then if that's the case would you agree if both are defined it should throw a usage error and exit? I can certainly toss that into the patch."}, {'account_id': 2696, 'date': '2015-06-12 16:00:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I'm not 100% what you're trying to do, overall.  Maybe some unit tests would clear that up?  (Surely testability was part of the reason this code is now in a nice "cli" module instead of some bin script.)'}, {'account_id': 7661, 'date': '2015-06-12 16:11:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

The problem I'm trying to deal with is the fact that storage policies REQUIRE the object ring to be named "object-x", where x is the index and that's where get-nodes looks for the index and uses that in the ls command section of the output.

The problem is if you were to build a ring with a different name (perhaps it an archived copy?) and run it through get-nodes you get a message that there is a mismatch with the ring and the ls commands are wrong because they don't include the policy in the directory names.  This patch includes that index as the policy even if the ring has a different name BUT also emits a warning that it has done so.

This is separate from the question about allowing the user to specify a ring and a policy in the command line.'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2015-10-20 21:13:11.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Abanoning based on the lack of activity since the last negative review. If you want to continue working on this, please reopen this patch.'}]

commit_message:
Make probetest validation work for EC

The __main__ in probe.common has historically supported a quick validation of
configured storage policies suitability for replication tests.  The new base
ProbeTest classes will select (or Skip) the test cases based on their ability
to find a suitable policy - but it won't tell you which policies are
configured that would be suitable - the __main__ in common can though.

Also make sure policy validation will use configuration of the replication
services to validate rsync endpoints.  This is a first step and making
probetests support seperate replication servers.

Change-Id: I2f1d5e0e805c052a396d6975bb43cc64994000d3

subject: Catch file open errors before calling ConfigParser
messages:
[{'account_id': 7661, 'date': '2015-05-29 14:58:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 7661, 'date': '2015-05-29 15:03:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

There are a number of utilities that require root access and rather than check, throw an obscure error message.  In the case of this, the message is

"Error: [swift-hash]: both swift_hash_path_suffix and swift_hash_path_prefix are missing from /etc/swift/swift.conf"

which is totally misleading.

Personally I'd like to see a consistent error message we can use for any utility requiring root access to run it.  I'm not wedded to the message this patch provides, which I wanted to keep simple, specifically:

you must be root to run this

feel free to suggest alternative messages'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2015-05-29 15:26:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

@Mark I can't reproduce i.e. root is not required. I believe the requirement here is to have read permission of /etc/swift.conf which on your system may be restricted to root?

The error message could be more helpful e.g. 'Unable to read config file <name>'"}, {'account_id': 7661, 'date': '2015-05-29 16:03:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

The open call has a try block, but the except statement explicitly ignores IOError, which is the error being thrown.  Shouldn't something explicitly be reported here?  Even something like "IOError trying to open foo" is better than silence.'}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2015-05-29 17:39:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

/etc/swift.conf is always restricted, because it contains a sensitive suffix.

But I do think that the right approach here is to do something about the error messages. It's not impossible to get them with Python .ini readers, but we have to stop doing ConfigParser().read("/etc/swift.conf"), if we do it. The right approach is this:

    cfgpr = ConfigParser()
    try:
        cfgfp = open(cfgname)
    except IOError, e:
        # This one contains the cfgname
        raise ConfigError(str(e))
    cfgpr.readfp(cfgfp)

The erroneous code is in swift/common/utils.py'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-29 18:18:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Catch file open errors before calling ConfigParser

The ConfigParser.read() does not have a way to distinguish between
syntax issues and file access issues. Fortunately, there is a way
to preserve the low-level error message by using .readfp() instead.

Change-Id: I39304f19d733f6ede1ccae69dd937449b5935e9e

@Minwoo Bae
It is not a problem to make one more settiongs variable, but - can you give me an example when we will need to set this values separately?'}, {'account_id': 9625, 'date': '2015-07-06 17:57:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Bogun. I'm looking at these lines here: https://github.com/eventlet/eventlet/blob/master/eventlet/wsgi.py#L265,L270

It seems to me that the expectation is that MAX_TOTAL_HEADER_SIZE is to be greater than MAX_HEADER_LINE, no?"}, {'account_id': 12631, 'date': '2015-07-06 20:03:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

ok.
What problem we will have if both MAX_HEADER_LINE and MAX_TOTAL_HEADER_SIZE will have same value?

Or better have unexpected behaviour when someone set option "max_header_size" in swift.conf and got error "too big header size"? It will happend if value of MAX_HEADER_SIZE(in eventlet.wsgi module) become bigger than MAX_TOTAL_HEADER_SIZE. Because variable MAX_TOTAL_HEADER_SIZE checked in completely independent way.

Event now, administrator can set MAX_HEADER_SIZE via swift.conf so it become bigger then MAX_TOTAL_HEADER_SIZE. Is it ok?'}, {'account_id': 12631, 'date': '2015-07-08 00:42:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Thiago da Silva

Can you give your vision on fixing the problem with header size limit? If my proposal is completely unacceptable.'}, {'account_id': 12631, 'date': '2015-07-09 17:53:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Is there any argumented objections?'}, {'account_id': 9625, 'date': '2015-07-10 19:33:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Bogun, I tend to agree with Minwoo, it seems like you should have to different settings in the config file'}, {'account_id': 12631, 'date': '2015-07-10 20:28:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hm... and you can describe situation when user/admin need both of this options?'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2015-07-10 20:44:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

The defaults in eventlet are 8192 per header line and 65536 overall. The limit in Swift are for 8192 per header line (which also sets eventlet's per-header-line limit).

Setting the total limit of all headers to the one-line limit is a bad idea. There are many headers that may need to be sent in the request and the total needs to be greater than just one header. For example, PKI tokens in Keystone can be multiple kB each. If an auth token is 8kB, we'll still need a lot more data in the request.

Please do not set the max total header size to the one-line limit.

Further, can you give a use case where this setting is necessary? What is prompting this change? What is broken today that this patch fixes?"}, {'account_id': 12631, 'date': '2015-07-12 23:55:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

In eventlet.wsgi we see:

MAX_HEADER_LINE = 8192
MAX_TOTAL_HEADER_SIZE = 65536

in swift.common.wsgi:
# Set maximum line size of message headers to be accepted.
wsgi.MAX_HEADER_LINE = constraints.MAX_HEADER_SIZE

So we can configure value of MAX_HEADER_LINE using option "max_header_size" in section "swift-constraints" in swift.conf.

Everything fine, until you try to set headers size limit to value bigger than 65536, because it will be limited by second limit MAX_TOTAL_HEADER_SIZE. Ant there is no way to change it via config, only patching the code.

Why I need it?.. this is perfect question... Because someone setup keystone with N regions and it produce keys that overflow all imaginable limits.

In any case if I don't see the code, and see option "max_header_size" in config, I will think this is limit for all headers. And current behaviour(maximum value have it's own maximum in 64k) will be big surprise. So we shouldn't set question "why this fix required for me?" but the question "should we stay unpredictable/unexpected behaviour?".

Again why for we need limit on 1 header? In any case if one header overflow MAX_HEADER_LINE or all headers overflow MAX_TOTAL_HEADER_SIZE the request will be dropped without any future processing.

Section 4.2 of rfc2068 says:

   HTTP header fields, which include general-header (section 4.5),
   request-header (section 5.3), response-header (section 6.2), and
   entity-header (section 7.1) fields, follow the same generic format as
   that given in Section 3.1 of RFC 822 [9].

rfc822 don't apply limit of header length too. 

Also not apache, not nginx, not lighttpd(as far as I remember) have option that limit size of 1 header. They have only option that limit whole headers block.'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2015-10-20 21:12:14.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Abanoning based on the lack of activity since the last negative review. If you want to continue working on this, please reopen this patch.'}]

commit_message:
FIX http header size constraint

eventlet.wsgi module contain 2 variable that controlling limit of HTTP
headers:
MAX_HEADER_LINE - limit the size on 1 header (one line).
MAX_TOTAL_HEADER_SIZE - limit the whole headers size.

Our code can configure only MAX_HEADER_LINE through
swift-constrains configuration section of swift.conf. This change set both
MAX_HEADER_LINE and MAX_TOTAL_HEADER_SIZE to our "max_header_size"
constraint.

Change-Id: I0fba3360892051720affe343d0b71aaa6edfed6e

Although perhaps the difference is useful?

I think I agree with Pete - just add it to additional info - it's a little bit more trixy on a parser, but should be just as good for quick visual inspection with greps?"}, {'account_id': 5600, 'date': '2015-05-23 23:16:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

This looks good to me - but regarding the trans_time vs. additional_info discussion, I'm concerned about putting metrics like that in what seems like an unstructured field. In a larger cluster it seems less likely someone will be grepping logs for individual requests. This seems more useful to look at in aggregate compared to app_time to find hotspots.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-15 00:25:41.000000000', 'message': 'Better storage server eventlet logging

The eventlet hub can be finicky - she doesn't like it when someone else is in
the spotlight (i.e. blocks).  When she's in a mood like this, sometimes she
won't hand accepted connections to the application as quickly as they're
accepted and you see a request log line from a storage server indicating the
response was "handled quickly" well after the proxy hit a timeout and moved
onto another server.  When this happens it's because the eventlet hub is being
starved by blocking operations in the app, but there's little insight into how
much impact this blocking is effecting the server's response time.

Refactor more common request routing into the base_storage_server.  Add
contextual start time to the WSGI environment captured closer to when the
eventlet.wsgi.server's accept returns a new connection.  Log something closer
to the real transaction time in the storage server logs in addition to the
time the request was "in" our app.

More often that not the logged trans_time will be only nominally longer than
the request_time - but when the eventlet hub is starved because of other
blocking operations it can be notably different.

Change-Id: Id1ee9551196b175d542b0990dff03d00c3c3a6b8
'}]
commit_message:
Better storage server eventlet logging

The eventlet hub can be finicky - she doesn't like it when someone else is in
the spotlight (i.e. blocks).  When she's in a mood like this, sometimes she
won't hand accepted connections to the application as quickly as they're
accepted and you see a request log line from a storage server indicating the
response was "handled quickly" well after the proxy hit a timeout and moved
onto another server.  When this happens it's because the eventlet hub is being
starved by blocking operations in the app, but there's little insight into how
much impact this blocking is effecting the server's response time.

Refactor more common request routing into the base_storage_server.  Add
contextual start time to the WSGI environment captured closer to when the
eventlet.wsgi.server's accept returns a new connection.  Log something closer
to the real transaction time in the storage server logs in addition to the
time the request was "in" our app.

More often that not the logged trans_time will be only nominally longer than
the request_time - but when the eventlet hub is starved because of other
blocking operations it can be notably different.

Change-Id: Id1ee9551196b175d542b0990dff03d00c3c3a6b8

The current commit message doesn't describe the bug very well.  directory markers *are* empty objects.  There's just a convention that they end in a slash (although a few clients probably expect the content-type application/directory).  OTOH, it is attached to the bug.

[{'created': '2015-03-17 15:39:47.000000000', 'message': 'Fix the Upload an object to a pseudo-folder

When you do:
$ swift upload container/pseudo-folder object
$ swift list container
Is shown this:
pseudo-folder
pseudo-folder/object

To avoid create a "pseudo-folder-object" empty
Like "pseudo-folder"
I create a conditional to put a "/" in the end of
the container string.

Obs: Work normally if you use these:
$ swift upload container obj
or
$ swift upload container/ obj

The problem occur when you don't write a "/" in
an upload of objects to a pseudo-folders
$ swift upload cont/folder obj
is different of this
$ swift upload cont/folder/ obj

commit_message:
Fix the Upload an object to a pseudo-folder

Avoiding upload an empty object to a folder.
Wrong: swift upload container/folder obj
Correct: swift upload container/folder/ obj

Change-Id: Icd9f4283686e156692e80419ea8fa0266ec81494
Closes-Bug: #1432734

commit_message:
Initial implementation for the storlets spec

This new middleware for Openstack Swift allows to
dynamically add compute functions along the pipeline,
without needing to explicitly add new middleware.

This implementation handles both the PUT and GET
requests, including the GET SLO case.

The class StorletGatewayBase in
swift/common/middleware/storlet_common.py defines
the interface which separates the swift side from
the compute engine side.
This initial implementation uses a stub gateway
implementation.

A code reference with a real (docker) implementation
can be found at:
https://github.com/Open-I-Beam/swift-storlets

*NOT* included in this initial patch and left for
amendment(s):
1.  the Unit tests
2.  The spec reviewer's suggestions/requirements

The spec is at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/164537/

First amendment done for fixing pep8 problems
Amendment2: further pep8 fixes. learnt to use "tox -v -epep8" and not "pep8"...

Change-Id: Ic129e922aed14133316199a0e59de04a03de49e7

subject: Add object undelete spec
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 597, 'name': 'Pete Zaitcev', 'email': 'zaitcev@kotori.zaitcev.us', 'username': 'zaitcev'}, {'_account_id': 1179, 'name': 'Clay Gerrard', 'email': 'clay.gerrard@gmail.com', 'username': 'clay-gerrard'}, {'_account_id': 6968, 'name': 'Christian Schwede', 'email': 'cschwede@redhat.com', 'username': 'cschwede'}, {'_account_id': 7847, 'name': 'Alistair Coles', 'email': 'alistairncoles@gmail.com', 'username': 'acoles'}, {'_account_id': 9625, 'name': 'Thiago da Silva', 'email': 'thiagodasilva@gmail.com', 'username': 'thiago'}, {'_account_id': 12193, 'name': 'Hisashi Osanai', 'email': 'osanai.hisashi@jp.fujitsu.com', 'username': 'ho'}, {'_account_id': 15343, 'name': 'Tim Burke', 'email': 'tburke@nvidia.com', 'username': 'tburke'}, {'_account_id': 16233, 'name': 'Mauricio Lima', 'email': 'mauriciolimab@gmail.com', 'username': 'limamauricio'}]
messages:
[{'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2015-02-12 17:40:41.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-12 17:54:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Build failed (check pipeline).  For information on how to proceed, see http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html#automated-testing

- gate-swift-specs-docs http://logs.openstack.org/21/155421/1/check/gate-swift-specs-docs/f178cb3/ : FAILURE in 1m 47s'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-02-12 20:34:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Sam and I had an idea that was more like the versioning middleware but would handle delete's too - maybe some other use cases.  It ends up looking more like a management middleware for doing object aliases/manifests in one "versioned" container to *real* objects in another container that sort of never get deleted.

Either he or I should work on updating this spec to include more detail and see if we can get some buy in.'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2015-02-17 17:14:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Very brief summary of a couple of *formative* thoughts I discussed with Christian in #openstack-swift, which relate more to the discussion at hackathon rather than content of this patchset.

1. Assuming we use a 'manifest' object to point to a 'real' object, and the manifest somehow manages the state (deleted or not) of the object, then the real objects will need to be stored in some-other-container. To avoid polluting the user account, some-other-container could be stored under a different account namespace using the same container/object name (so no issues with name-length constraints).

e.g. PUT AUTH_id/c1/o1 would result in a manifest at AUTH_id/c1/o1 pointing to the real object at HIDDEN_id/c1/o1

Both manifest and real object have timestamp t0.

2. service tokens *might* help here with managing access to the HIDDEN_ account prefix (think of undelete as a 'service' - the middleware has access to a service token meaning it can create/delete in the HIDDEN_ account in conjunction with user token, but user token alone cannot access HIDDEN_).

3. When an object is deleted at t1, the manifest in AUTH_ is deleted using timestamp t0_t1 (reconciler-type two vector timestamp) but the real object is left in HIDDEN_

4. If undelete is required at time t2, a privileged user (having a service token) can list HIDDEN_ to 'discover' 'deleted' objects, and PUT a new manifest to AUTH_ using timestamp t0_t2. The undeleted object will appear to the user to have timestamp t0 (i.e its original timestamp) in both the manifest and container listing. The offset _t2 is sufficient for the 'undelete' PUT to supersede the DELETE."}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2015-05-07 08:03:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2015-05-07 08:06:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

A few smaller updates to this spec:

- re-used the original template
- added an alternative
- renamed the spec

I'm more and more interested in an alternative solution based on ACLs restricting allowed verbs instead of moving around data, creating manifests and refactoring hash_cleanup_whatever ideas.

So, at the end there might be restricted accounts that can't delete / overwrite existing data."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-07 08:09:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-swift-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/21/155421/2/check/gate-swift-specs-docs/91477be//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 55s'}, {'account_id': 12193, 'date': '2015-05-07 10:00:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I understand that this spec is useful for some cases.
I have a concern about usage of extra storage space. These options need to have extra storage space so it is better to have explicit trigger to do it. So I put -1 for this.

If possible, I would like to discuss about the goal for this spec in summit.
I think it is not possible to protect data completely if there are abused credentials and/or buggy application. The traditional way for this is "data should be backed up by users/operators" and required storage products to having backed up and restore functionality. 
My points are 
* explicit trigger of enabling backup which is used by users/operators
* confirm whether the data is valid (not accidental deletion) by users/operators
* explicit operation of restoring data which is used by users/operators'}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2015-05-07 10:07:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Thanks Hisashi for your comments!

I agree on the extra storage space requirement - that's why I renamed the spec and added an alternative solution. So, having users that are only abled to do PUT/GET/HEAD (maybe POST) in combination with object versioning should solve most if not all problems to prevent accidental deletion.

I don't think backups are a viable option though - Swift itself is more often than not used for backups itself; having a backup for a backup storage seems awkward to me? 

Also, backing up large cluster might be impossible at all, and then there is always a window without a backup (if you don't copy every object immediately somewhere else):

- Backup at time t0
- Object stored at t1
- Object modified/deleted at t2
- Backup at time t3 (for example 24 hours later)

From reading the spec I think the idea of preventing delete can actually be provided by two different "features" with slightly different use cases:

1. This is basically a revamp of object versioning with the ability to version a delete too, such that you could actually have versions for object 'foo' like this:
  v1: t0
  v2: t1
  v3: t2 < This is a delete 
  v4: t3

2. Provide the ability to restrict ACL for certain users, such that they can create and get objects but never delete.

I see these use-cases as two different features, maybe we need two specs???'}, {'account_id': 9625, 'date': '2015-06-25 20:11:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2015-08-11 21:55:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Adds capability to specify config file

This commit adds a widget that allows for file or direct input of
VDU config values during VNF creation. This will bring VNF creation
via horizon in parity with what is currently available in
python-tackerclient

Change-Id: I828a6f5787484a17b1590e144798e25d00a2bfd9
Closes-Bug: #1493558

commit_message:
Prevent to decode with invalid ec scheme

Basically, we must not deploy overwrite the ec policy scheme
if we have already have some objects in the policy becuase
absolutely we won't be able to get the correct data from the
Swift with the overwritten policy.

However, in the such a case, current Swift would return the garbage
(i.e. decorded but incorrect object) and user might not find the fact
it is the garbase, unfortunately.

To prevent the situation, this patch adds a validation that
the swift could decode the FAs correctly.

TODO: Create validater for other similar stuffs (e.g. ec_segment_size)

Change-Id: I4e4955341f78c3eda68890a75d3a8f59322543ef

commit_message:
change deprecated assertEquals to assertEqual

fix against H234: assertEquals() logs a DeprecationWarning
in Python3.x. use assertEqual() instead.And the same, change assertNotEquals() to assertNotEqual().

Closes-bug: #1489031

commit_message:
bin directory: :Replace python print operator with print function (pep H233, py33)

'print' function is compatible with 2.x and 3.x python versions
Link : https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-3105/

Python 2.6 has a __future__ import that removes print as language syntax,
letting you use the functional form instead

Change-Id: I379b47c63fd80b617fe4d5972f1d6a0ebee941c4

commit_message:
go: pass vars to container update

Since we kick container updates out to a background goroutine and let the
request handler return, the vars context can be cleared before GetVars is
called.

That means means it doesn't know what device the request was for when saving
asyncs, and it just dumps it into the device root.

Change-Id: I8fff740fa470b9d5012864ed92c8d0767efcb519

commit_message:
go: CopyN that re-uses buffers

Include an implementation of CopyN that reuses buffers, to reduce pressure on
the GC.  Also clean up Copy with new libraries from go 1.5.

Change-Id: Ie8247aa608b6c472a5e5ffde915637aca10f099f

The change adds Keystone v3 support to neutron l3 ha tool. This
change is needed to ensure that all l3-ha fail overs are
accomplished correctly.

The tool has been updated to skip / support routers that have
already bene setup using the built in neutron L3HA.

This is something that will need to be backported to Kilo

Change-Id: I94f21ff3fa511bc9da6b57cdf847719620818ece
Closes-Bug: #1499708
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>
