commit_message:
Updated the neutron l3HA tool to use v3

The change adds Keystone v3 support to neutron l3 ha tool. This
change is needed to ensure that all l3-ha fail overs are
accomplished correctly.

The tool has been updated to skip / support routers that have
already bene setup using the built in neutron L3HA.

This is something that will need to be backported to Kilo

Change-Id: I94f21ff3fa511bc9da6b57cdf847719620818ece
Closes-Bug: #1499708
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>
(cherry picked from commit 2108d7fe03427eb9cb6c52a4edd4755582f05fe7)

I have a comment that is applicable to all the changes, but I was wondering if domain should be

https://git.openstack.org/openstack

instead of

commit_message:
Make a few IP methods private

We're getting close to a 1.0 release, and these methods have terrible
interfaces. They're also not used anywhere. So let's make them private
for now, and if we find a time in the future where we need to expose
them, we can do that.

Change-Id: I357dbc0c2e61a5b9f62bfbd45595992d7eb21909

Create neutron floating ips with server info

When we create a neutron floating IP with server port information,
then we don't need to do a separate attach step.

commit_message:
Add API for container create, delete, list, show

This patch adds basic API calls for Containers, as well as the testing
infrastructure necessary to test these API calls.

Also adds some basic testing for Bays and Bay Models.

Change-Id: I7cb5dfbd32695c95a414b8d41aa0aa178fe2472e
Implements: blueprint container-api

[{'created': '2015-10-20 07:04:07.000000000', 'message': "Additional RabbitMQ SSL fixes

This patch fixes two problems with RabbitMQ's SSL/TLS listener.

* When self-signed certificates are used, the CA cert isn't created, but it's
  included with the RabbitMQ server config anyway (bug 1507364).

* Self-signed certificates are owned by root within RabbitMQ's configuration
  directory and are unreadable by RabbitMQ. User-provided certificates aren't
  affected (bug 1506992).

Closes-bug: 1506992
Closes-bug: 1507364

Change-Id: If4f6a325eea4772f2fad4604785241b67adfaaf6
(cherry picked from commit d7031f954de7d73a96c303aed8b6e1f4441c03b0)
"}]
commit_message:
Additional RabbitMQ SSL fixes

This patch fixes two problems with RabbitMQ's SSL/TLS listener.

* When self-signed certificates are used, the CA cert isn't created, but it's
  included with the RabbitMQ server config anyway (bug 1507364).

* Self-signed certificates are owned by root within RabbitMQ's configuration
  directory and are unreadable by RabbitMQ. User-provided certificates aren't
  affected (bug 1506992).

Closes-bug: 1506992
Closes-bug: 1507364

Change-Id: If4f6a325eea4772f2fad4604785241b67adfaaf6
(cherry picked from commit d7031f954de7d73a96c303aed8b6e1f4441c03b0)

commit_message:
Move session and fixtures to keystoneauth1

in an effort to start consuming keystoneauth1, we can move our
sesssion and fixture code over to use keystoneauth1 instead of
keystoneclient.

[{'created': '2015-10-20 16:55:42.000000000', 'message': 'Make designate record methods private for now

The API for designate is not something we can commit to right now. It
turns out that v1 has Domains and Records and v2 has Zones, RecordSets
and Records. Figuring out an API design that can handle both is not
going to happen before 1.0, so mark the current Record API as private
so that we can add something we can commit to later.

Change-Id: Ia2611f19d04a2d7a51d85ac99f19ed4054972085
'}]
commit_message:
Make designate record methods private for now

The API for designate is not something we can commit to right now. It
turns out that v1 has Domains and Records and v2 has Zones, RecordSets
and Records. Figuring out an API design that can handle both is not
going to happen before 1.0, so mark the current Record API as private
so that we can add something we can commit to later.

Change-Id: Ia2611f19d04a2d7a51d85ac99f19ed4054972085

subject: telemetry: add alarming tests in 'smoke' suite
messages:
[{'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2015-10-20 18:43:54.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2015-10-20 18:49:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

So I don't think this is the right path. Mostly because all the ceilometer tests are going to be extracted into a plugin before too long. We want smoke to be a minimal set and since ceilometer in general isn't even viewed as in scope for direct testing anymore I don't think it fits in that minimal set.

I think this will be fine after we make it a plugin."}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2015-10-20 18:57:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

what if we want to run the tests now, without waiting for ceilometer team to move the code into a plugin?'}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2015-10-20 19:00:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

You can just leverage a different test selector which is more inclusive than just a regex of 'smoke'. If it's getting a bit unwieldy on the CLI I'd recommend looking at ostestr's whitelist file option which lets you dump a bunch of different regexes in a line separated file"}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2015-10-20 19:05:21.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

[{'created': '2015-10-20 18:43:54.000000000', 'message': "telemetry: add alarming tests in 'smoke' suite

Testing Alarming is really important when testing Ceilometer, Aodh and
Gnocchi.

Without alarming tests, there is no way to test Aodh in 'smoke' suite.
This patch adds the decorator so Alarming tests are part of 'smoke'
tests.

Change-Id: I74b4f76d94b838e2fa5dbbbaed80d28341327f64
"}]
commit_message:
telemetry: add alarming tests in 'smoke' suite

Testing Alarming is really important when testing Ceilometer, Aodh and
Gnocchi.

Without alarming tests, there is no way to test Aodh in 'smoke' suite.
This patch adds the decorator so Alarming tests are part of 'smoke'
tests.

Change-Id: I74b4f76d94b838e2fa5dbbbaed80d28341327f64

commit_message:
specify runtime environment for scripts

I68200a23c87ceca5a237da13d9549c0aa82f1b8f has changed two scripts
to be executable, but unfortunately, it forgets to specify runtime
environment for those scripts, which will cause error when trying
to run those scripts directly.

This patch adds python environment specification for them.

Change-Id: Ibbcefb671de76146529b9a6e2debfee154a1aaa7

commit_message:
Rescue boots to SMS

Previously, the PowerVM power_on Job was broken for bootmode='sms', so
the rescue flow skipped this step, leaving it to the user to boot to SMS
manually.  The power_on Job now works, so this change set restores the
boot step to the rescue flow.

Change-Id: I71e28dcbb96ae580ac3ebb54582eee9a039b9ae6
(cherry picked from commit 2deaae0fe59abffbca6f7b156bcc805ea4e0e11f)

'}, {'created': '2015-10-15 18:51:38.000000000', 'message': 'Switch to post-versioning

No longer mention next version on setup.cfg on stable branch.

oslo.utils 2.6.0 causing tox test to hang.
This forces a specific version of oslo.utils *before* the
requirements are loaded, thus ensuring that 2.6.0 is *not* used.

commit_message:
Switch to post-versioning

No longer mention next version on setup.cfg on stable branch.

oslo.utils 2.6.0 causing tox test to hang.
This forces a specific version of oslo.utils *before* the
requirements are loaded, thus ensuring that 2.6.0 is *not* used.
(This is a temporary fix until oslo.util pushes a new version.)

Depends-On: Ica981756c67902e7fd7bd07ff76c5b679e8e4e2f
Change-Id: I97ec9d17b6a611d888ef007575a29c1811f475c9

commit_message:
LIO: Let delete_initiator succeed if iqn not found

When performing delete_initiator, this should not
raise an error if it can't find the initiator in
an ACL.  This likely indicates something has
gotten out of sync, but the teardown should be
allowed to succeed.

Closes-Bug: #1506496
Change-Id: I3fa9d2e4a435de7c8ee5b24d419930050af197fe

commit_message:
Initial wwpn only valid if no existing WWPNs

The 'is_initial_wwpn' was simply looking at the fabric state and task
state.  However, if multiple BDMs were specified on a deploy, this would
cause multiple WWPNs to be generated for the same fabric (because each
would be considered 'initial').

This change set expands the logic to also check if any WWPNs have been
set on the fabric yet.  If so, it is not considered an initial WWPN.

Change-Id: I03767f406e004349015483ef8b696f72c57d8ede
Closes-Bug: 1507774
(cherry picked from commit a5995ffc2d5c4ee91bd045ebb2f0ea6ed0deca8d)

Thanks for the comments guys. I'll respond here because the response is more holistic response than specific to the lines of text. 

In this specific case, the errors I experienced were due to "apt-get install python-tox" installing older versions. It was hard to troubleshoot because the problem wasn't with tox itself but some of the tox dependencies. The errors were resolved by upgrading to the latest versions using pip. However, thinrichs was concerned that by instructing people to use the latest versions, things may break if/when in the future the devs release a non-backward compatible version. I think we've experienced problems in some other cases. (see inline comments in patchset 1).

There is a tension between the desire to use the latest version and the desire to avoid the possibility that a non-backward compatible version a released and breaks things. 

How about this for a compromise:

1. In instructions for initial install of tox (line 9), don't use a specific version.
2. In the instructions for troubleshooting errors (lines 10-17), suggest to the users that using these specific tested versions may resolve their issues.

That way it's only in a case where something doesn't work do we suggest specific versions which may not be the latest.'}, {'account_id': 8878, 'date': '2015-10-16 15:48:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

IMO, My experiences indicate that it's no need to specify a version which works well. Docs would just have wrong version list which don't work if user uses the version. commit_message:
hadoop: move scripts from post-install.d to install.d

As also the previous comment on the top of 40-setup-hadoop said, this
was done because the Hadoop v1 RPM was buggy, so it needed to be
installed after the rest of the system is set up.

Since the support for Hadoop v1 has been dropped, the installation of
Hadoop can be done in install.d.

Change-Id: If3b0f8f595d6bf36017e63d331b5c1f7faa532e2

commit_message:
Fix incorrect federated mapping example

The documentation didn't provide correct example of a mapping rules with
direct group mapping (with blacklist/whitelist keyword).
This could led users to a major confusion.

The example is now fixed. Additionaly, for clarity and increased
readibility the ``user`` and ``groups``
objects were split into separate ``local`` rules.

Change-Id: Iff343f1ff2829ef282a1314fd07203a435611e70
Closes-Bug: #1507944

commit_message:
Huawei driver handle volume exists error

Currently when we create a volume on an array
where that volume already exists,
there will be an exception. But in fact it should
just go on and doesn't need an exception.

Closes-Bug: #1504718
Change-Id: I13a52e81c1c271ea6728cb4a23717609d95bae69

commit_message:
Search for existing aodh binary

The os_aodh role fails to run when aodh_venv_enabled is set to false.
This is because the role searches for an aodh binary which does not
exist.  This commit updates os_aodh to search for aodh-api instead,
which is a valid binary installed by aodh.

Change-Id: Ic64d1cb8a301c0716e6cd05554b7806847769472
Closes-Bug: #1508052

commit_message:
Added DevStack plugin for Congress

The copy/paste model is the old model, at present
all shared services are enabled in DevStack through
plugin. So a plugin is added in this patch

Change-Id: I2e9ce1130dea9e5a724787adb893f5b8a710dc62
Implements: blueprint implement-plugin-model

commit_message:
Fixes TLS processing in the rest driver

The rest driver was not using updated cert utils to
handle processing of TLS certificates and would cause failures.

Also updates build_pem to be py34 compliant.

Change-Id: I05db39ff673083649735434f8e4cc710086ffd54
Closes-Bug: #1507723

commit_message:
Unretire the stackforge/networking-bigswitch repo

The maintainers for stackforge/networking-bigswitch misunderstood
the stackforge namespace retirement and move announcements and did
not realize their repository would be retired in the recent
maintenance. Restore it for now until it can be batched into a
future rename maintenance.

Change-Id: Id66cd51c5c526d8e1869bbaaedc5c0f9be886daf

commit_message:
[perestroika] Inject perestroika into fuel-mirror

While we have migration of perestroika to Python implementation
we need to have friendly and open way to share and fix issues
in current perestroika code

Change-Id: I7fced52ddadc81d4d8a52659358936f6e68cc3e4
Closes-bug: #1489470

commit_message:
List federated projects from keystoneauth

Handle the EmptyCatalog exception raised from the
keystoneauth1.access.service_catalog.url_for
function in the unscoped token case.

Also make sure AUTH_INTERFACE is passed in from
keystoneauth1.plugin not keystoneclient.auth.base
so that it passes the check at
keystoneauth1.identity.base.get_endpoint. This
particular change covers the non-federated
project listings also.

Co-Authored-By: Paulo Ewerton Gomes Fragoso <pauloewerton@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Closes-Bug: #1471943
Change-Id: Ia2d38fb612f54472a7ccca17b4da2590ed0c4f32

commit_message:
add "registry" flag to "tools/build.py"

With registry flag,
build image using `tools/build.py --registry 172.22.2.81:4000`
the image name looks like `172.22.2.81:4000/kollaglue/data`
When user use kolla-ansible,
user set `docker_registry` to `172.22.2.81:4000` in `/etc/kolla/globals.yml`.

Build image using `tools/build.py -n abcd`
the image name looks like `abcd/data`
When user use kolla-ansible,
user set `docker_namespace:` to `abcd` in `/etc/kolla/globals.yml`.

build image using `tools/build.py -n abcd --registry 172.22.2.81:4000`
the image name looks like `abcd/data`
When user use kolla-ansible,
user set `docker_namespace:` to `abcd` in `/etc/kolla/globals.yml`.
user set `docker_registry` to `172.22.2.81:4000` in `/etc/kolla/globals.yml`.

With the feature, it will reduce user confusing and mistaking.

Change-Id: I18ac7a3ccec032888e35f5e9a79fc190760cc8a0
Closes-Bug: #1505056
(cherry picked from commit 52b72538114fdf3de5b71ce399bb0992d2748d75)

commit_message:
Cinder client does not expose error details

Keystone raises exception if the HTTP response code is >=400.
This however doesn't include the error description. The error
message can be included just by adding response.text to
formatted_string variable.

Change-Id: I10ce3348b0f3a33bbe976962660a7c7ed599b254
Closes-Bug: 1412583

commit_message:
Reduce checks for migration wwpn in npiv

The NPIV code would check both the task state and the host attribute to
determine if the WWPN was used for migration.  However, the only check
that needs to be done is the host.  If the instance is not on the new
host, it should use the secondary WWPN.

This change relaxes the code to fit this model.

Change-Id: I314a1a794a47b239b7a882acf327b24f56e1e356
Closes-Bug: 1507018
(cherry picked from commit 23d06863c221d211910edec9d1ee69ac34239fd2)

commit_message:
Use Barbican gate_hook in preparation for removal of extras.d

Barbican supports DevStack's plugin method, so the Barbican client
gate jobs should use it, instead of the old method which is
deprecated.

Change-Id: Ic5da694ff2daab2b958899cb0fa676dce30976f4

commit_message:
Add grenade to PROJECTS list in grenade jobs

This will allow us to remove grenade from the default PROJECTS list
since it is only required when running grenade.

commit_message:
add config option to point to the cgit browser

Add a configuration option to let projects set the URL to the cgit
browser for their source. Still try to guess at the location based on
our git URL.

Change-Id: I11455f8a137a029c28a864eb555f69f6c282840b

commit_message:
Speed up kafka plugin

Contruct one kafka consumer per consumer_group/topic cobination
This should significantly reduce the collection time

Additionally, this removed the ability to specify partitions to
collect. It will accept both old and new config formats, but
will always collect info from all partitions for a topic

Change-Id: Ib8e1b24ce515a0635e7e6cc4f6537e80f66b161c

commit_message:
Add a ceilometer-functional job for mysql

Add a ceilometer-functional job for mysql to run alongside the
postgresql and mongodb jobs, initially as an experimental job.

This job was probably supposed to be there all along, its absence an
oversight. Once it is confirmed to be happy a followup patch will
put it in gate and check.

Change-Id: I334db9864e1295b968847f646966b27556949d7b

'StackViz'.

Rename identity_domain to domain

Since designate renamed domains to zones (or is going to), we can
just call keystone domains "domain" without a prefix of identity.

commit_message:
Rename designate domains to zones

In anticipation of the Big Rename, rename domains to zones. This helps
be less conflicty with keystone.

Blueprint: the-big-rename

[{'created': '2015-10-20 15:06:11.000000000', 'message': "Don't log error on expected condition.

When deleting a port, we first try to delete a special logical switch
which will exist if this was a port on a provider network.  This is
expected to raise an exception in the non-provider network case.  We
shouldn't log an error here.

Change-Id: Ib4ccd0b0325e43094107c0b29b7e6da7d94ce91f
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>
"}]
commit_message:
Don't log error on expected condition.

When deleting a port, we first try to delete a special logical switch
which will exist if this was a port on a provider network.  This is
expected to raise an exception in the non-provider network case.  We
shouldn't log an error here.

Change-Id: Ib4ccd0b0325e43094107c0b29b7e6da7d94ce91f
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Check RBDConnector.disconnect_volume device_info argument

device_info is optional and in some cases could be None.
We should check it and don't fail in case if it is None.

Add failure percentages in text to the gauges

This commit makes it possible to see what is the proportion between
passes and failures.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-16 17:59:34.000000000', 'message': 'Generic driver: wait for common server during setup

If the driver does not handle share servers, during init, it
verifies that the pre-configured share server exists and is available
(behavior recently introduced by
I325d6461c4b12f481769bb01f792ef850dba789c).

If the instance does not exist when the service starts, the driver
will remain permanently in an uninitialized state, even if the
according instance is created meanwhile.

This patch changes this behavior, waiting for the common server
to become active, logging a meaningful message. This can considerably
ease the deployment of this driver as well as other drivers based
on it.

At the moment, the Windows SMB driver CI jobs fail due to this issue,
when DHSS is set to false (in which case the Nova Hyper-V nodes are
deployed after Manila).

Change-Id: Icf446ca25cf0c64396223611c6271d4c6445cb4d
Closes-Bug: #1506951

commit_message:
Generic driver: wait for common server during setup

If the driver does not handle share servers, during init, it
verifies that the pre-configured share server exists and is available
(behavior recently introduced by
I325d6461c4b12f481769bb01f792ef850dba789c).

If the instance does not exist when the service starts, the driver
will remain permanently in an uninitialized state, even if the
according instance is created meanwhile.

This patch changes this behavior, waiting for the common server
to become active, logging a meaningful message. This can considerably
ease the deployment of this driver as well as other drivers based
on it.

At the moment, the Windows SMB driver CI jobs fail due to this issue,
when DHSS is set to false (in which case the Nova Hyper-V nodes are
deployed after Manila).

Change-Id: Icf446ca25cf0c64396223611c6271d4c6445cb4d
Closes-Bug: #1506951

commit_message:
Enable cmd/api & cmd/conductor to be launched directly

This will be needed for functional testing, so we can execute them with:
  python -m ironic.cmd.api
  python -m ironic.cmd.conductor

Change-Id: I2f201ee1f6517879fec6da4e6f40a6155763d979
Partial-Bug: #1491670

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Adding 'json_pp' function in YAQL

 * Added new function called 'json_pp'
   for pretty output json objects using YAQL.
   It can be used, for example, for sending email
   containing some dicts or lists.
 * This function also fixes escaped new-line symbols

Change-Id: I8a7d432a957423b832935f46bb04ddd4505258c7

Given that documentation is an indication of support, I'd like to ensure we have two things before we claim support here:

A) Someone should independently test such a deployment to ensure this documentation is accurate.

B) We should ensure that there is sufficient interest in the use case prior to committing keystone-core to maintaining this documentation.

If (A) is a challenge, then (B) probably isn't likely. If that's the case, then would be a better fit for another venue, such as a blog post or wiki page."}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2015-03-17 15:50:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

For (A), if someone wants to propose a branch to https://github.com/dolph/keystone-deploy exercising federation / ABFAB, that'd be fantastic and I'd be happy to maintain it moving forward."}, {'account_id': 15638, 'date': '2015-03-17 16:23:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1

I have validated the documentation and made ABFAB authentication work following it.

@Brant. Two points on your comment

1. The admin guides (at http://docs.openstack.org/admin-guide-cloud/content/) does not contain anything about federated identity as far as I can tell, nor about SAML or OIDC


2. The developers guide already contains info similar to the current spec, e.g. for OIDC is contains http://docs.openstack.org/developer/keystone/extensions/openidc.html


Given the above it would appear to me that the ABFAB instructions belong in exactly the same place as the OIDC ones, and that both should be in the developers guide.'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2015-04-27 15:05:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Instructions to install IETF ABFAB federation protocol on Keystone

Add instructions to the documentation on how to install the
apache plugin for abfab, and configure it to work with keystone.

implements bp abfab

Change-Id: I65f7d4fccc74757bb87b0757e1f084f2685a96f1
Co-Authored-By: David Chadwick <d.w.chadwick@kent.ac.uk>

commit_message:
Allows for reset of dependency injections

Currently dependency injections cannot be reset as they are registered
in a list that is never cleared. For test cases, this is a broken
mechanic. This patch clears the dependencies list in the reset method
used for unit testing.

Change-Id: I8a437d541e5e338bb17b02718061ac9a92ed9da8
Closes-Bug: #1295280

commit_message:
Updated docs for Keystone startup

Removed all mentions of keystone-all from installing.rst and developing.rst
docs.

keystone-all is being phased out for it has not been updated in the master and
not accessible in the current version. This fix is important because it
provides users with an easier way to run Keystone.

In developing.rst, in place of the keystone-all setup there is now
a detailed tutorial on how to run Keystone with Eventlet and also HTTP under both Fedora
and Ubuntu operating systems. In installing.rst there is an updated reference to developing.rst on
how to run Keystone using the above methods.

Change-Id: Idc7649179867f66a9db873b8daa5f86e48f4b920
Co-Authored-By: Akshay Aggarwal <akshay.onweb@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Chloe Jensen <cjensen17@jesuitmail.org>
Closes-Bug: #1462242

commit_message:
Improving readability of OSTF results in system-tests output.

Create function pretty_log which makes log in table format.
Use this function instead of json.dumps() in fuel_web_client.py

Change-Id: I299ec5f26c888d18bbf525c075cb391beeff1950
Closes-Bug: #1506506

commit_message:
Add anti-XSS horizon vhost options

New header values:
Header X-XSS-Protection "1; mode=block"
Header set X-Content-Type-Options nosniff
Header always append X-Frame-Options SAMEORIGIN

Disabled directory index listing.

Added spec for openstack::horizon

Fixed fixtures+git refs to run openstack::horizon
in rspec correctly.

Change-Id: I50eb6104134f98fa61283f8ddda7449f92e99783
Closes-Bug: #1496407

Change-Id: I22ecff14ba7a16d441f7b5e2b525cf5d9c8aa146

[{'created': '2015-10-20 13:12:14.000000000', 'message': 'Set neutron_lib_dir depending on neutron_venv_enabled

When neutron_venv_enabled is set to false, neutron fails to deploy as
it cannot find the alembic_migrations dir.  This is due to neutron
being installed in dist-packages outside of the venv and site-packages
inside the venv.  This commit adjusts neutron_lib_dir depending on
whether or not neutron_venv_enabled has been set.

Change-Id: I9d992993b116e85216c07d6fdb6a4f99398a2102
Closes-Bug: #1508041
'}]
commit_message:
Set neutron_lib_dir depending on neutron_venv_enabled

When neutron_venv_enabled is set to false, neutron fails to deploy as
it cannot find the alembic_migrations dir.  This is due to neutron
being installed in dist-packages outside of the venv and site-packages
inside the venv.  This commit adjusts neutron_lib_dir depending on
whether or not neutron_venv_enabled has been set.

Change-Id: I9d992993b116e85216c07d6fdb6a4f99398a2102
Closes-Bug: #1508041

commit_message:
print sample id for query-samples

Provide sample id can make it possible for end user to query particular
sample by its id, this is needed because we don't show everything in
the list.

Change-Id: I06bfc2de1a4e9a24892b2e36b6d2137e1b38cb27
Closes-Bug: #1506745

commit_message:
fix typos in docstring

patch I4804c45c2ba69982163503ba5d9d4eba86f904fe has some typos in
docstring:

* :param *args: should be :param args:, there is no need to use the
  leading star, meanwhile the star has special meaning in doc string
  which need to appear by pairs.
* :param for this ceiloclient, actually this phase is part of last
  param's help string

Change-Id: Ib7b964ffe064b805130953f6a6abca354d9eef79

commit_message:
Fix missing ironic_url variable in config drive role

The ironic_url variable was being satisfied by another role,
and upon attempting to execute the roles separately, it was
found to be missing the variable.  Added variable default
and README text entry.

Change-Id: I1ff56d1081ed92ae21a9729e40d94e9550bf710b

commit_message:
nova: set catalog_info to InternalURL

In nova.conf, set cinder/catalog_info to 'volumev2:cinderv2:internalURL'
instead of 'volumev2:cinderv2:publicURL'.
So Nova will use internal Cinder endpoint to reach volume API by
using internal network.

Depends-On: Id9e579ca31364d5207d0c1b892d0f7aa7f20f7a8
Change-Id: Ia34f0fe59f662c3ad29ca0178c01ef1570759d57

commit_message:
Fix random gate breakages due to cleaning

After pxe_ssh got support for cleaning, it now takes substantial
time to get from manageable to available, we need to accound for it.

Also simplify debugging of gate issues:
* Show node info before failing due to provision state not reached
* Shorten retry timeout for enroll->manageable transition to 1 minute
* Report nova hypervisor-stats before failing

Closes-Bug: #1508001
Change-Id: Ic11bd20509b726b1ff2d3a7edd63479e9b79486e

commit_message:
Proxy configuration for agent images downloading

This spec proposes support of HTTP(S) proxy configuration for agent.
Agent will use proxy parameter during images downloading.

Change-Id: I173821fff2324c9cda77c6af5f6dd7561e16b18e

commit_message:
Adds cert_manager option to octavia.conf

[{'created': '2015-10-15 11:49:45.000000000', 'message': 'mocking sendfile to make the test run on OSX

The test case intention is to exercises the _download method of
BaseImageService by asserting that having downloaded an image, the image
content and the download target file content are the same.

Since a regular file target is being used, the test case fails on OS X (10.11)
where the sendfile syscall requires a socket as a target file descriptor [1][2]

The suggested patch intention is both to preserve the sendfile syscall in the
BaseImageService._download method (because of performance reasons[3]) as well
as make it possible to run the unit tests on OS X. This is achieved through
asserting on relevant call patterns rather than call effects by
mocking/patching the necessary system facilities: open, os.path.getsize and
sendfile.sendfile.

[1] man sendfile OS X 10.11 (10-2015)
[2] _download method implementation, ironic/common/glance_service/base_image_service.py
[3] simple benchmark results, pysendfile home page https://github.com/giampaolo/pysendfile  online 10-2015

Change-Id: Ia907751d6d9eebb59f5ef6899da30b4c79628582

The test case intention is to exercises the _download method of
BaseImageService by asserting that having downloaded an image, the image

The suggested patch intention is both to preserve the sendfile syscall in the
BaseImageService._download method (because of performance reasons[3]) as well
as make it possible to run the unit tests on OS X. This is achieved through
asserting on relevant call patterns rather than call effects by
mocking/patching the necessary system facilities: open, os.path.getsize and
sendfile.sendfile.

[1] man sendfile OS X 10.11 (Oct 2015) [2] _download method implementation,

ironic.tests.unit.drivers.modules.irmc.test_deploy.\
  IRMCDeployPrivateMethodsTestCase.test__parse_deploy_info_ok

The test case intention is to exercise the irmc_deploy._parse_deploy_info
function by asserting that provided irmc_boot_iso file exists, the function
parses the input into an expected structure. For that purpose the test case
utilises /etc/fstab file which it assumes to be always present. Unfortunately,
on OS X (10.11, Oct 2015) this file is no longer present by default.

The suggested patch intention is to assert os.path.isfile was called with
expected irmc_boot_iso path.

Closes-Bug: #1329077
Change-Id: Ia907751d6d9eebb59f5ef6899da30b4c79628582

commit_message:
mocking syscalls to make the tests run on OS X

ironic.tests.unit.common.test_glance_service.TestGlanceImageService

The test case intention is to exercise the _download method of
BaseImageService by asserting that having downloaded an image, the image
content and the download target file content are the same.

Since a regular file target is being used, the test case fails in OS X (10.11)
where the sendfile syscall requires a socket as a target file descriptor
[1][2]

The suggested patch intention is both to preserve the sendfile syscall in the
BaseImageService._download method (because of performance reasons[3]) as well
as make it possible to run the unit tests on OS X. This is achieved through
asserting on relevant call patterns rather than call effects by
mocking/patching the necessary system facilities: open, os.path.getsize and
sendfile.sendfile.

[1] man sendfile OS X 10.11 (Oct 2015) [2] _download method implementation,
ironic/common/glance_service/base_image_service.py [3] simple benchmark
results, pysendfile home page https://github.com/giampaolo/pysendfile, Oct 2015

ironic.tests.unit.drivers.modules.irmc.test_deploy.\
  IRMCDeployPrivateMethodsTestCase.test__parse_deploy_info_ok

The test case intention is to exercise the irmc_deploy._parse_deploy_info
function by asserting that provided irmc_boot_iso file exists, the function
parses the input into an expected structure. For that purpose the test case
utilises /etc/fstab file which it assumes to be always present. Unfortunately,
on OS X (10.11, Oct 2015) this file is no longer present by default.

The suggested patch intention is to assert os.path.isfile was called with
expected irmc_boot_iso path.

Closes-Bug: #1329077
Change-Id: Ia907751d6d9eebb59f5ef6899da30b4c79628582

>Kevin, the operator use case here is achieving scale whle servicing individual requests. Therefore, batching requests is off the table.

I don't buy that as a valid excuse. If the agent is falling behind on requests, that means requests are queuing up. If requests are queueing up, that means that they can be batched. It will be significantly more work to batch them, but batching is by no means 'off the table'.

This patch keeps the status quo of processing events one at a time so we basically just kick the can down the road a little further until someone adds another syscall that lands us in exactly this same spot. 

Additionally, now we will have two performance profiles (one for a system that has a secured netns directory, and one for a system that doesn't). Guess what information we will now have to collect every time someone reports a performance issue with an agent?

Finally, it's not clear that this will do anything to address the bug report. On my dev laptop, ensure_namespace can create about 3 per second (with 500 namespaces already present). It can make about 4 per second if it doesn't check for existence at all. The bug report is talking about a degradation creating routers so I fail to see how this patch addresses the reported bug.

The reason I marked the bug as incomplete is because it was a bad bug report. It offered a suggestion for a way to do something differently but it didn't show that this was the major reason for a degradation at scale. There is no acceptance criteria for a fix other than blindly doing what the submitter suggested.

I really dislike working on performance improvements this way because we are doing micro-optimizations without an idea of how much we're helping in the long run... in case you couldn't tell from the rant above. :)

If we are checking if namespaces exist that frequently, we should just stop checking if they exist and write an exception handler that detects errors from them not existing and automatically create them."}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-10-02 00:34:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Code-Review-1

Sorry, I rambled too much on my last comment. Here are my two issues:

* major performance difference for root and non-root case.
* bug report doesn't have any information showing that this will be a significant improvement to router creation.

If we can't show this will make a major difference to router creation, it's not worth two different code paths. If it does, I will be fine with this patch although I am going to follow up with the complete removal of this check."}, {'account_id': 9970, 'date': '2015-10-02 01:32:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

@Kevin:

- I don't understand how batching up operations can be used to address this issue.  If you currently have 3000 routers and are running just fine.  Let's say you attempt to add router 3001 and it takes n minutes to occur.  Some time later, admin adds router 3002 is added and it takes another n minutes.  We are not adding 1000 routers at once here.  This issue was with adding one router after already having 1000 created.     

- Yes, there is a performance difference between root / non-root cases.  There is a also a significant performance difference between native python os.listdir() and a external command call to run "ip netns" and to scrape the output string.

- You are correct.  The bug report did not list specific time stamp measurements for this performance issue.  I don't think we can require individuals opening bugs to report detailed stats like that.  I was grateful to the author of the bug to point out methods in the code where there are performance issues rather than just stating performance is bad when doing operation X.  I think the author of the bug was also very helpful in making suggestions on things that could be done to improve the performance of this code path.  I think that is above and beyond what is expected.  What was listed in the bug report were 2 possible suggestions on things that could be done differently.  I investigated those items as well as several other changes before ending up with the current patch.  The current patch actually does not do either of the original suggestions from the bug report.

- Will this change make a huge difference in the time it takes to create routers when there are 100s or 1000s of them?  No, it will probably won't.  There are other far worse issues with OVSDB for example. Will this minor change help with performance... yes, I think it will. 

- As far as two different router creation methods, don't we already have that we the "use_helper_for_ns_read" that was introduced on the earlier bug?  I wanted to remove that config option entirely and get to a single code path with the try/catch version (PS #7), but that version was rejected and it was suggested that the config option be used (PS #9).'}, {'account_id': 9970, 'date': '2015-10-02 02:11:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

@Kevin

"... I will be fine with this patch although I am going to follow up with the complete removal of this check."

Can you please elaborate?'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-10-02 07:41:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: -Code-Review

>Let's say you attempt to add router 3001 and it takes n minutes to occur.

ensure_namespace doesn't take n minutes to occur though in any of my testing, and that's with thousands of namespaces. It takes < 1 second. So the only way I can see that this would be an issue is if you had hundreds of router creation requests back-to-back so the agent can't keep up.


>Yes, there is a performance difference between root / non-root cases. There is a also a significant performance difference between native python os.listdir() and a external command call to run "ip netns" and to scrape the output string.


Yes, that's the problem. I don't want a massive different between these two options if possible.


>The current patch actually does not do either of the original suggestions from the bug report.

No, but it optimizes the specific method that was identified in the bug report. The issue with optimizing methods at this level is that it's very vulnerable to regression during refactors since it's not attached to any particular use case.

I understand that the author put a lot of work into code profiling, but it would have been easier for the author and better for us to have a report that said something along the lines of "after 4000 routers, it takes 5 minutes to create a router", because that has an obvious user impact and it gives us room to optimize lots of stuff. With the current report, we are backed into a corner and we can't tell if it's making a broad impact (i.e. we're shaving time off of something that takes a small percentage of the total router creation time).

>I wanted to remove that config option entirely and get to a single code path with the try/catch 

Right, that would penalize the case that requires root helper with another filesystem call in addition to what it currently does. The fact that we are currently forcing a choice between security and performance is pretty sad. We don't want to make it worse.


I'm not going to block this anymore. I'll propose my alternative approach and if people don't like it we can continue down this path.'}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2015-10-02 09:14:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

@Kevin:

> ensure_namespace doesn't take n minutes to occur

I agree. It doesn't. I never said it did.  I am going to try getting precise performance measurements for this specific code path today.

> I don't want a massive different between these two options

Ideally it would be best to only a single option was used, but I'm not sure how to accomplish that:

Option 1: Remove the performance path and force all distros down the slow path
Option 2: Remove the slow path and drop support for those distos which lock down: /var/run/netns

I don't see how either of these are valid choices. 

> I understand that the author put a lot of work into code profiling, but it would have been easier for the author and better for us to have a report that said something along the lines of "after 4000 routers, it takes 5 minutes to create a router", because that has an obvious user impact and it gives us room to optimize lots of stuff. 

Multiple bugs have been created on the Liberty/router/L3/L2 performance issues.  There are probably some bugs out there written up in a vague fashion like you are suggesting.  This specific patch is not the largest hitter in this code path, but all of the little performance enhancements will add up. 

> With the current report, we are backed into a corner and we can't tell if it's making a broad impact (i.e. we're shaving time off of something that takes a small percentage of the total router creation time).

I don't expect this bug/patch to make a large difference in the total router creation time.  There are other bugs/patches that will have a larger impact when they get fixed/merged.  All of the smaller performance enhancements will add up.

> The fact that we are currently forcing a choice between security and performance is pretty sad. 

This patch does not add a choice between security and performance.  That choice was already added several releases ago by the original bug that added that "use_helper_for_ns_read" config option.

> I'll propose my alternative approach 

I look forward to seeing it.'}, {'account_id': 9970, 'date': '2015-10-02 13:52:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

[{'created': '2015-09-24 23:34:19.000000000', 'message': 'Improve performance of ensure_namespace

The ensure_namespace method calls IpNetnsCommand.exists to
determine if the specified namespace exists or not.  This is
accomplished by listing all namespaces with "ip netns list"
and then looping through the output to determine if the specified
namespace was included in the output.

Research of various Linux operating systems has indicated that
namespaces are represented as files in /var/run/netns AND root
authority is not required in order to look at the files in this
subdirectory.

Rather than swapping to root and gathering a list of all namespaces,
it is more efficient to just check for the namespace file object
in /var/run/netns.

Closes-Bug: #1497396
Change-Id: I9da627d07d6cbb6e5ef1a921a5f22963317a04e2

commit_message:
Improve performance of ensure_namespace

The ensure_namespace method calls IpNetnsCommand.exists to
determine if the specified namespace exists or not.  This is
accomplished by listing all namespaces with "ip netns list"
and then looping through the output to determine if the specified
namespace was included in the output.

Research of various Linux operating systems has indicated that
namespaces are represented as files in /var/run/netns and root
authority is "typically" not required in order to look at the
files in this subdirectory.

The existing configuration option "use_helper_for_ns_read"
will be used to determine if the root-helper should be used to
to retrieve the list of namespaces.  If this configuraton option
is set to False, the native python os.listdir(/var/run/netns)
will be used.

Related-Bug: #1311804
Closes-Bug: #1497396
Change-Id: I9da627d07d6cbb6e5ef1a921a5f22963317a04e2

commit_message:
Fix for deleting VM when VNF is deleted

This commit adds code to fix the issue of VMs not getting deleted
when deleting VNFs in PENDING_CREATE or ERROR state.

Change-Id: Idac5ecc80fb78805f0642e4c08cc73a24640d6bd
Closes-Bug: #1475798

Bharath, thanks for taking care of this issue. After IRC discussions with sridhar_ram and you, few more things to be taken care of as part of closing this bug:
1. Can we handle the config_boot_wait and config_boot_wait_max_timeout options for retrying the configuration. That way we can ensure the mgmt driver tried connecting few times to update the config before finally giving up.
2. We will have to handle the above options specific to a single mgmt driver as the boot_wait can vary for each of the mgmt drivers. For now, this would be in openwrt.py Also we need to remove the hard coded sleep of 30 seconds in config_device method. 
3. Looks like both mgmt driver and heat are trying to update the config on VNF instance. We do not want heat to handle the config update and it should be done only by mgmt driver. So we need to remove the code (L290 - L304) in heat.py'}, {'account_id': 12455, 'date': '2015-10-14 05:16:29.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-14 05:21:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Escape yaml string to configure VDU

Use 'unicode_escape' to escape YAML while configuring
VDU at the time of vnf-create or vnf-update using --config
flag

Change-Id: Ia4543b9437f28b4e6312bbd2fab9a7c47dd9f610
Partial-Bug: #1501079

commit_message:
Always drop lxc_net bridge configuration

This patch makes sure that the lxc_net play does always write the
LXC bridge-interface configuration regardless of it's admin state.
This is particular important after we deactivate the lxc-net
systemd script as part of the LXC network configuration.

Closes-Bug: #1507795
Change-Id: I9547fe02e20e8d1690340e1193b2453997ada25c
(cherry-picked from commit a0ec97553198c432db8f0d4f6b99936221ce53df)

commit_message:
Destroy previous test env VM's earlier

Destroying these earlier will ensure we don't get logs from the
seed if disk-image-builder fails in cases where the seed VM was
left behind running from a previous ci test.

Change-Id: Ia73e635da303533a0f37b4c1574788966a94475f

commit_message:
Use 'python-murano-dashboard' for dashboard_package_name

Need to fix Murano dashboard package name
according to its naming in Debian and Ubuntu:
https://packages.debian.org/experimental/python-murano-dashboard
http://packages.ubuntu.com/wily/python-murano-dashboard

Hey All, just wanted to leave a quick update; I chatted with Tim on IRC and like his suggestion (it required a minor tweak), so at this point we have:

Write Crypto Meta:

- The decode of the b64 encoded data is required in py3 only (but doesn't hurt py2) as json expects a str (i.e. unicode) not bytes (which is what encoding produces)

req.headers['X-Object-Sysmeta-Crypto-Meta'] = json.dumps({
key : (base64.b64encode(value).decode() if key == 'iv' else value)
for key, value in body_crypto_meta.items()})

Read Crypto Meta:

- The 'str' call is required (maybe) because in py2, loading a json object returns unicode not ascii, whereas the crypto meta dictionary should use whatever the native str type is (so in py2 that's ascii, and in py3 that is unicode which is what the json load produces anyway) 

crypto_meta = { str(key) : (base64.b64decode(value) if key == 'iv' else str(value)) for key, value in json.loads(crypto_meta_json).items()}


No regressions with the above except a bunch of unit tests are failing, but the reason is clear:  The failing decrypter unit tests are assuming the header is simply base64 encoded (which is no longer the case it is a json obj where one of the values happesn to be base64).

Should have code in a day or so.   I'm also testing on the most recent patch set and found other similar issues, so I'll fix everything required for this patch, and then hopefully we can merge this into crypto branch, and then rebase the others (and I'll fix anything new)"}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2015-10-02 22:09:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

(1 comment)

On the crypto meta, I like the plan! I wouldn't worry much about calling str() on read yet; I'm not sure it's necessary and it feels like we're getting ahead of ourselves on the py3 front. I just wanted to point this out to make sure we didn't make the eventual addition of py3 support more work than it has to be."}, {'account_id': 17156, 'date': '2015-10-03 03:44:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

(1 comment)

Thanks Tim !  But I actually feel the str conversion during the load is safer for the py27 code (i.e. right now).  Otherwise what happens is the dictionary is not all the sudden:
{iv : iv_val, crypto_mode : crypto_mode_val}

=>

{ unicode, binary, unicode, unciode }

Wheras originally it was:

{ str, binary, str, str } 

So by calling str we're sure the string values in the dictionary are always the native type (i.e. py27 => str) which matches the originally dictionary.


Now if it matters or not I'm not so sure : )  That is, so what if in py27 the dictionary now uses unicode after the decrypter reads the json crypto header.  But this seems safer.

Let me know if you have other thoughts though !"}, {'account_id': 17156, 'date': '2015-10-04 16:52:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 15.'}, {'account_id': 17156, 'date': '2015-10-04 16:54:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

Hey All, the patch set above implements the changes I described.

FYI:
This is going to require more changes on the more recent crypto code;  The reason being we now encode / decode in many different places (as opposed to the two in this patch set) i.e. for user meta / container meta / ...

I plan on fixing this my adding a util function to encapsulate the encoding and decoding of crypto meta (in a json object), and simply call this throughout.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-04 17:28:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15: Verified-1

commit_message:
Encrypter and Decrypter middleware - object body only

See encryption spec in_progress/at_rest_encryption.html

Adds the encrypter and decrypter middleware.  This middleware
is only handling the encryption of the object body at this point.
There will be another review for metadata.

Depends on having keymaster middleware and cryptography module.
You can point the following vagrant to this patch:
https://github.com/swiftstack/vagrant-swift-all-in-one/tree/crypto
Alternatively, please follow the instructions
in the proxy-server.conf-sample.  You will also need to add the
fake_footers middleware as well to get the correct functionality.

Currently, the functests have 4 errors and 17 failures.  These
are all due to not having COPY implemented, and not having a good
solution for handling conditional GET.

Change-Id: If5f83a9e6f5b9166015e6988e43101e4e69a6e65

Change-Id: I9ee06658d49163f041df18a62b33fa2804f545b8

commit_message:
Using oslo-config-generator to instead of generate-config-file.sh

We don't need a separate script to wrap the oslo-config-generator. Like
other projects, we can just specify a config-generator config file to
define the namespaces.

Change-Id: I9ee06658d49163f041df18a62b33fa2804f545b8

commit_message:
[shotgun] Create run_tests.sh

This file is used by fuel-ci to run tests. In order to
put shotgun into a separate repository we need this file
to be in the directory.

Related-Bug: #1506894
Change-Id: I70bafc87819cbba006baacd7de80f1f1e274167f

commit_message:
Make secgroup rules refresh with refresh_instance_security_rules()

The refresh_instance_security_rules() call was introduced to make
security rule refreshes be specific to a single instance instead of
refreshing rules for all instances on a host[1].

A couple of places that still use the old call can be changed to the
more efficient one and the old refresh_security_group_rules() method
can be removed since it now becomes unused.

[1] Commit: 2afbbab23a9d845cde511baa1e574fdcf5ab5171

Change-Id: I3b0b9e5ad02057649564a7aec895b98f35a70cd9

commit_message:
Remove unused refresh_security_group_members() call

This call was replaced with refresh_instance_security_groups() in
compute rpc version 1.41(!) Since we just reached version 4.0 it
should be fairly safe to just remove all traces of this without
backwards compatibility being an issue.

The original change that replaced and made this call no longer being
used was commit 2afbbab23a9d845cde511baa1e574fdcf5ab5171.

Change-Id: I60d314f68a984fa8e6d36f46b5ae595f0afabe73

commit_message:
DVR: Notify specific agent when update floatingip

The L3 agent was determined when update floatingip.
So notify the specific agent rather than notify all agents.
This will save some RPC resources. This is only for DVR routers.
Legacy and HA routers notify only the relevant agents.

Partial-Bug: #1486828
Change-Id: I12f61afdfaa944bc4b659cec61a8b5ff8c66ae76
Co-Authored-By: Oleg Bondarev <obondarev@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Remove non-existent enable_tunneling conf from fullstack

enable_tunneling is not actually a conf option, fullstack
config fixture code was passing it to the OVS agent but
it doesn't do anything.

Change-Id: I4fbe20c37f3ca6395c1ac43123a3cc2338065ed1

commit_message:
QoS SR-IOV: allow to reset vf rate when VF is assigend to VM

delete_bandwidth_limit method is called in 2 scenarios:
1. when deleting a port
2. when removing a policy from a port

self.eswitch_mgr.clear_max_rate is valdating if VF is not assigned to VM
which is good for case 1, but prevent reseting the max rate for case 2.
for case 2 the delete_bandwidth_limit should  call _set_vf_max_rate with max_kbps=0
to reset VF max rate for assigned VM.

Closes-Bug: #1504165

Change-Id: Ief708531708b8faa918603298d49d39ef5ba2df5
(cherry picked from commit 2e0ead8e043a47db214f4f52c9bfe71b6079b5fd)

I don't know the requirements (from which this review has been appeared), but I don't agree with this patch. IMO, it doesn't support widely used conventions (which could be confusing for the unix users). I'm giving "0 No score" because I'm not sure and don't know all details.

Very often unix applications doesn't rely on any config file. You can remove all config files and application will be operating using default settings (hard-coded in application). I haven't seen before such a thing as a *default* config file. By convention a unix application may be looking for a config file in /etc/, $HOME, $PWD directories. Settings which are defined in $HOME/configrc have higher priorities than settings which are defined in /etc/configrc. And settings from $PWD/configrc have higher priorities than from $HOME/configrc. Also settings could be defined via environment variables (which has highest priority). IMO, these all described things are good conventions for a unix application.'}, {'account_id': 6623, 'date': '2015-10-16 13:15:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

Andrey, thank you for your review. What you've described is indeed the right way to do it. However, we cannot just change it here on the client side. commit_message:
Generate user settings file

Since relying on a system-wide /etc/... configuration
file is not a good approach for a user-side application
it's necessary to not use that file by default.

This patch changes default settings file to ~/.config/fuel/fuel_client.yaml
and adds generation of one with default values if it does not exist.
Specifying of a custom settings file using FUELCLIENT_CUSTOM_SETTINGS
variable is still possible.

DocImpact
Closes-bug: #1458361
Change-Id: Ia17c8edbdd71a74318d3237a47d4b5650934c378

commit_message:
Retry metadata request on connection refused error

This testcase may fail intermittently on 'Connection refused' error.
This could be due to the fact that the metadata proxy setup is not exactly
complete at the time the request is issued; in fact there is no
synchronization between the router being up and the metadata request being
issued, and clearly this may be the reason of accidental but seldom failures.

In order to rule out this possibility and stabilize the test, let's retry
on connection refused only. If we continue to fail, then the next step would
be to dump the content of iptables to figure out why the error occurs.

Closes-bug: #1461172

Conflicts:
	neutron/tests/functional/agent/test_l3_agent.py

Change-Id: I65a5bf4fbbcad6ba93a46d36cabe7844ff528d8d
(cherry picked from commit 4b2e6842f320405cd963f560bc06849b4b7bb1eb)

commit_message:
Fix iptables comments for bare jump rules

This fixes the order of arguments in iptables rules that
are bare jumps (e.g. '-j other-chain').

The previous code was only catching jump rules that appeared
after a chain definition.

Closes-Bug: #1502932
Change-Id: I490792eb08c67a32f9b286d933a776fb76840b6b
(cherry picked from commit 2a4b5f938d038bd73a70f1fc86cc71e819e288b0)

commit_message:
The exception type is wrong and makes the except block not work

According to the context, it should be KeyError here to catch.
AttributeError will not happen here. More details could be found
in the bug report.

Change-Id: Id6351172703ac492e86475f75bf1be03f4e4e8a3
Closes-bug: #1506934
(cherry picked from commit 9d6584120003f50782461677d1b783bd07131444)

commit_message:
Rely on devstack for clouds.yaml

devstack makes clouds.yaml in /etc now so each project doesn't need
to copy it.

Depends-On: I21d3c2ad7a020a5ab02dc1ab532feae70b718892

commit_message:
Remove placeholders from being displayed

This removes the Placeholders section from the main specs page.
We need to have the old URLs available so that external references
to them still work, but we don't want to encourage people to use
those links.

Change-Id: I4d237f85518bce699c20cb3720faec5233272c92

commit_message:
Fix rule generation for single and all host rules

iptables outputs single-host rules with a prefix on the
end (/32 or /128) and completely omits /0 rules since they
allow everything.

This patch fixes our rule generation to match that pattern
so iptables counters don't get destroyed on these rules on
every reload.

Closes-Bug: #1502917
Change-Id: Ifbdfbafd6cf37c6ef7385cd5f1d2df65cc19797a
(cherry picked from commit 9f620772f0097156858255687ed97128ef666825)

wrapped against it's natural formatting.

Change-Id: Iaf81d310f9406a23539efc3a3e2f25034ae39fa8

commit_message:
tests: Allow for code block lines to be longer

Currently tests would fail if code block lines are longer than 79
characters, which is too restrictive as code blocks can contain
JSON or shell (or any other) code which should not be artificially
wrapped against it's natural formatting.

Change-Id: Iaf81d310f9406a23539efc3a3e2f25034ae39fa8

commit_message:
Assign networks based on template

When a node is added to a cluster with a network template
networks will be mapped to NICs based on transformations
in the template. Any bonds will be created in the database.
Any time the cluster's network template is changed the NIC
mapping will be recreated.

Change-Id: I2b52444f3019241362e5a957bf191645b94ebaa7
Closes-bug: #1493391

commit_message:
Update tox.ini and fix py34 issue

This commit updates tox.ini to support py27 and py34 versions
which are gate tested and also fixes the issue of
'db type could not determined' thrown while running tox.

Change-Id: I77cb87c6f7ba6eaa609e40e83eb9bdab3b8b0283

commit_message:
Fixed the method name reference in instancespage

In instancespage.py: changed self._wait_till_spinner_disappears()
to self.wait_till_popups_disappear()

Partially implements blueprint: selenium-integration-testing
Closes-Bug: #1507816

Update notes about the Neutron teams

Provide links to who belongs to what team, and
rename the section to better reflect its content.
Add the Neutron drivers team, which apparently
was missing and only captured on the wiki.o.o.

Fix lint job errors

This commit fixes lint job errors that were recently introduced by
change I42e9b73c55a1a5372401ed64e0e3f60cb57ea696. Since the job isn't
voting yet this was missed. However, the patch is in progress to make
it voting, so we should fix this with some alacrity.

cause multiple WWPNs to be generated for the same fabric (because each

commit_message:
Initial wwpn only valid if no existing WWPNs

The 'is_initial_wwpn' was simply looking at the fabric state and task
state.  However, if multiple BDMs were specified on a deploy, this would
cause multiple WWPNs to be generated for the same fabric (because each
would be considered 'initial').

This change set expands the logic to also check if any WWPNs have been
set on the fabric yet.  If so, it is not considered an initial WWPN.

Change-Id: I03767f406e004349015483ef8b696f72c57d8ede
Closes-Bug: 1507774

commit_message:
Only bind mount images dir /w local Glance storage

/var/lib/images should not be bind mounted unless:
The glance server is not on metal
Is using local file storage
Isn't using glance_nfs_client settings

This isn't required for non-file backed glance servers, and will cause
failures if /var/lib/images is bind mounted when using nfs_clients
for glance.

Closes-bug: #1503411
Change-Id: Ie90f75652a960af664fcf8f29d554045f0599944
(cherry picked from commit 537912778d8c79ffe54930612077e2bea72de737)

commit_message:
Correct flavors API docs for compute api

There isn't sub-resources 'os-flavor-rxtx' under 'flavors', this patch
removed it. And also use all_extensions api sample instead of only flavor
enabled api sample files, because the nova v2.1 API must enable all
the extensions.

Change-Id: I98da27dd616fe829e9f1d8e9ad6cb58eb5660597
Closes-Bug: #1506281

commit_message:
Validate src_ip_adress, dest_ip_address and ip_version

The FwaaS API should not allow the creation of firewall rules where
the ip_version is set to 4, but the source or destination IPs are IPv6
addresses

DocImpact
